<HEADLINE> German Daimler Expects 50 Percent Rise in Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest industrial group
Daimler-Benz today predicted an at-least-50 percent increase in its
operating profits this year.
</P>
<P>
The Stuttgart-based company said that its turnover through
September reached 87.6 billion marks (50.1 billion U.S. dollars), up
15 percent from the same period last year, and that for the year as
a whole, the figure would reach about 120 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
This is compared with the 115 billion marks previously projected.
</P>
<P>
The company expected its second-half operating profits to exceed
first half's figure of 1.85 billion marks. This would bring the
overall result this year to at least 3.7 billion marks, over 50
percent more than the 2.4 billion marks in 1996, which was achieved
on turnover of 106.3 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
The higher profit came from improved result in car division, the
traditional pillar of company earnings, as well as in truck production
sector and in its aerospace unit Dasa, according to Daimler.
</P>
<P>
At Mercedes, private car revenues rose by 13 percent to 38.3
billion marks through September, with car sales up 6.5 percent to
512,000, while commercial vehicle turnover registered a surge of 20
percent to reach 278.6 billion marks, with sales up 20 percent to
298,000.
</P>
<P>
1.7 German mark is equivalent to one U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
