<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Blood Pressure Mishandled in Canada, Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- As many as 3.5 million Canadians
have high blood pressure that isn't being treated, and at least
1.4 million of them even don't know they have it, a new study
says.
</P>
<P>
Canadian doctors are partly to blame for not being more
aggressive at diagnosis and treatment since high blood pressure
raises the risk of death from heart attack and stroke, according
to the study.
</P>
<P>
Cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of death in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"To be blunt, physicians haven't come up to speed on the
guidelines. We should be doing much better," said the study's
author, Dr. Michel Joffres at Dalhousie University in Halifax.
</P>
<P>
General guidelines for high blood pressure is a level above 140
over 90, which represents the amount of force the heart must put
on blood to move it through the body.
</P>
<P>
There are 4.1 million people in Canada with hypertension, and
only 600,000 of them are adequately controlling their blood
pressure, the study estimates.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a million have tried to control it and either have
stopped taking medicine or have slipped back into poor diet and
exercise habits.
</P>
<P>
Among those who are treated, many don't receive regular
follow-up, the study found.
</P>
<P>
And few were given advice on lifestyle changes that might
reduce blood pressure, including losing weight, getting more
exercise, eating more fruit and vegetables and reducing sodium
intake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
