<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Speakers' Conference Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A three-day conference of
speakers and parliamentarians of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) concluded here today with the
adoption of a number of proposals on cooperation and development.
</P>
<P>
The conference unanimously approved the recommendations made by
participants on "promotion of people-to-people contact and closer
inter-action through parliamentary institutions" and on the "role
of parliaments and parliamentarians in population and
development."
</P>
<P>
At the conference, speakers from the seven SAARC member
countries -- India, Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Maldives, Nepal, Sri
Lanka and the host country Pakistan -- reaffirmed their desire to
address the issues of population and development with the ultimate
aim of improving the quality of life of their people.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing after the conclusion of the conference,
Illahi Bukhush Soomro, speaker of Pakistan's National Assembly,
expressed his hope that the governments of the South Asian region
will implement the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The conference recommended that the member countries relax visa
restrictions to allow free movement of their citizens in the
region for closer cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the promotion of people-to-people contact and
population welfare and development were the focal subjects of the
conference.
</P>
<P>
According to Soomro, the conference also recommended a South
Asian student dialogue for students and youth from universities of
SAARC countries to meet and deliberate on various issues.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for the exchange of data through E-mail
on the Internet, so that parliamentarians in all SAARC countries
are kept posted on the latest developments in each other's
parliaments.
</P>
<P>
It was also recommended that editors, writers and journalists
from the member countries convene annually to discuss
media-related matters, particularly the free flow of information.
</P>
<P>
The conference also called for efforts to ensure easier access
to books, periodicals and newspapers as well as other publications
in SAARC countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the conference recommended the exchange of SAARC
TV programs and a weekly TV program called "SAARC Hour" between
SAARC countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
