<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Ruling Party Begins Breakup, Opposition to Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 28 (Xinhua) -- While South Korea's ruling party
today appeared to break up over the nomination of party leader Lee
Hoi-chang as the presidential candidate, two opposition parties
agreed to make leading opposition leader Kim Dae-jung the single
candidate in the presidential election scheduled for December 18.
</P>
<P>
After Lee Hoi-chang, president of the ruling New Korea Party
(NKP), declared his break with President Kim Young-sam, the
party's anti-Lee faction is considering bolting from the party
unless Lee resigns as the NKP presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
NKP advisor Lee Man-sup, a former NKP chairman, resigned as NKP
lawmaker and left the party today.
</P>
<P>
Even some of Lee's supporters in the NKP showed signs of
turning against nominating him as the NKP candidate, doubting
whether Lee's sagging approval rating can able his victory
against 'DJP alliance' in the coming election.
</P>
<P>
The DJP alliance is a coalition of the two major opposition
groups, the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) led by Kim
Dae-jung and the United Liberal Democrats (ULD) led by Kim
Jong-pil.
</P>
<P>
A breakthrough came Monday night when Kim Dae-jung secretly
visited Kim Jong-pil at his home and endorsed what their deputies
had negotiated concerning the single candidacy and ways of sharing
power after winning the election.
</P>
<P>
"Everything has come to a successful end. The only procedure
left is signing the accord," said Kim Dae-jung, adding that an
official announcement would be made on November 3.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports on their pact on the formation of a
coalition government with power equally shared by the two parties,
once Kim Dae-jung wins the election, Kim Jong-pil will become the
first prime minister with strengthened powers to control the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties also agreed to revise the constitution
by 1999 to introduce a German-style parliamentary system of
government, in which a strong premiership reduces the presidency
to a figurehead post.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP leader said he made the concessions in a bid to help
achieve a transfer of power from the ruling to an opposition
party, which has not occurred for decades in South Korean
political history.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that the opposition, boosted by the
alliance between the two parties, has the greatest chance of
winning the upcoming presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
