<HEADLINE> French Minister Says Stock Market Crisis Won't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Industry,
Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn said today that the
on-going world-wide stock market crisis will not hit the economic
growth of France and other European countries.
</P>
<P>
"In France as in Europe, the resumption is there, it is solid
and profound," said Strauss-Kahn at the French National Assembly
(parliament) when answering questions about the stock crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that the consequences of the stock market crisis on
"the real economy" will remain weak, and that the hypothesis on
an economic growth in France will not be jeopardized by it.
</P>
<P>
The French stock exchange index, CAC 40, fell by 8 percent this
morning soon after the Paris Bourse opened, amid falls in other
European markets and New York.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Southeast Asian nations are widely
blamed for the stock crisis which is hitting Europe, the United
States and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
"But one should stay very careful about the evolution,"
Strauss-Kahn added, saying that the balance of the French stock
market depends on its liquidity and solventness.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the on-going crisis in Southeast Asia and
Hong Kong is "a crisis of adjustment after a very strong growth"
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the countries and regions in crisis should seek a
solution in collaboration with international institutions, such as
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
