<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakh Economy Grows Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Kazakh economy grew
steadily in the first nine months of 1997, with the industrial and
agricultural output rising 3.6 percent and 1.5 percent
respectively over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output reached 593 billion tenge (about 7.8
billion U.S. dollars) during the period, according to the latest
economic report released by the Kazakh State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural output amounted to 230 billion tenge (about
3.03 billion U.S. dollars) in the January-September period, among
which the output of crops stood at 146 billion tenge (about 1.9
billion U.S. dollars), increasing 8.5 percent over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's foreign trade in the first eight months
of this year dropped one percent to 6.673 billion U.S. dollars
from the same period last year, mainly due to the decline of its
foreign trade with the CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States)
countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's foreign trade with the CIS states in the
January-August period accounted for 53 percent of its total,
dropping from the 74 percent in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Kazakhstan's inflation rate remained
at 7.1 percent in the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
