<HEADLINE> Rybkin Urges New Security Area in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Ivan Rybkin, Secretary of the
Russian Security Council, said on Monday that it is possible to
build a new security area from Vancouver to Vladivostok.
</P>
<P>
The concept, first advocated by Russia in 1995, is seen as
Moscow's counter-measure to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's eastward expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin said in his meeting with visiting members of the Foreign
Policy Committee of Germany's Federal Assembly that Russia should
play a role in building the new trans-Atlantic security area, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been advocating a European security system based on
the European Security and Cooperation Organization. The nation
fears that NATO's expansion into its eastern borders could
threaten its security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
