<HEADLINE> Canadian Public Endorses Radical Steps to HIV Rise, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are generally willing
to endorse radical steps to drug addiction and AIDS-virus
infection, according to the head of a national task force.
</P>
<P>
There is widespread public recognition about the failure of
current policy, Dr. Catharine Hankins told a national conference
on HIV and AIDS in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
"Most people in Canada know someone who has done drugs" and
want to see more effective responses to the spread of HIV among
drug users, she was quoted as saying by reports today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the task force released a report that called for
decriminalizing heroin, increasing methadone treatment and
allowing widespread commercial availability of clean needles to
reduce the risks of contracting the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
Cutting the spread of the disease among users through the
controversial methods is a first step to curbing health costs,
which is in the national interest, she said.
</P>
<P>
HIV among injection-drug users in increasing by at least 2,500
cases a year across Canada and the direct cost of treating the
victims exceeds 100,000 dollars (72,000 USD) a person annually,
according to the task force.  
</P>
</TEXT>
