<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Overhauls Insurance Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has taken measures to
restore order to the insurance industry in order to provide
qualified service for people.
</P>
<P>
A revised insurance law stipulates that the registered capital
of an insurance company must amount to at least 3 billion leva (17
million U.S. dollars) by the end of March 1998.
</P>
<P>
The companies that also deal in the reinsurance business are
required to have a registered capital of at least 4 billion leva
(23 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
This measure will force a number of small insurance companies
to either merge into other companies or go out of business.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of the country's insurance market is
controlled by around five insurance companies out of about 120
insurance companies in Bulgaria. Many small companies sell
insurance illegally and often use violence.
</P>
<P>
The State Insurance Institute, the biggest insurance company in
the country, will be transformed into a holding company with a
registered capital of 35 billion leva (200 million dollars)
divided into 3.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians and concerned government staff are not allowed
to be members of the board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
