<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Government Condemns Coup Attempt in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government today strongly condemned the foiled coup in Zambia,
saying that it supports the Zambian government's measures to
defeat the plotters and assert its authority.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly condemn the illegal attempt to seize power in
Zambia," the South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Acting
Foreign Minister Valli Moosa, as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement was also read in the National Assembly in Cape
Town.
</P>
<P>
"Our government views the attempted coup d'etat in the
Republic of Zambia in a very serious light, considering it
unconstitutional and unacceptable action against a democratically
elected government," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Acting President Thabo Mbeki has been in touch with various
leaders in the region to discuss this matter, Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
They included Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, Southern
African Development Community (SADC) Chairman Robert Mugabe and
South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said South Africa also took the opportunity to reaffirm
the commitment of the SADC region to act in defense of democracy
and the protection of human rights, as well as against the
seizure of power through the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen for all of South Africa's opposition parties in the
National Assembly said they support the government position.
</P>
<P>
Zambian rebel military officers led by Captain Steven Mungu
stormed the Zambian National Broadcasting Corporation this
morning and Mungu announced that a military junta had taken over
the power.
</P>
<P>
The coup failed when his forces was thwarted by troops loyal
to Chiluba, who told the nation that he is in full control of the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
