<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASE to Tighten Foreign Listing Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Alberta Stock Exchange (ASE)
of Canada is tightening listing rules for foreign operators to
help prevent stock market fraud like Bre-X Minerals Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"With foreign junior mining and energy companies, because of
the difficulties in getting information, we are going to set a
higher hurdle rate," ASE president Tom Cumming was quoted as
saying by a report today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, foreign issuers must have tangible assets
of at least one million dollars (720,000 US dollars), up from
500,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
They must also have adequate internal controls to ensure
proceeds from share offerings are spent as disclosed.
</P>
<P>
And at least two directors must be Canadian with an
"acceptable" level of public company and industry specific or
technical experience.
</P>
<P>
The new rules will come into effect on November 1, according to
today's Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Calgary-based exchange has been pondering tightening the
rules, and the Bre-X fiasco, probably the largest market fraud
ever, increased its resolve. Bre-X started on the ASE.
</P>
<P>
The ASE defines a foreign issuer as a company whose principal
assets, proposed business and controlling shareholders or
management are located outside Canada.
</P>
<P>
Some five percent of its listed companies fit that category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
