<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Selling Rocket Technology to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Russia today denied that it had
sold rocket technology to Iran, describing the allegations as
"groundless reprimands" most probably concocted by Israel and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky told a briefing
here that rumors to this effect "most often come from two
sources: Washington and Tel Aviv."
</P>
<P>
There was, is and will be no cooperation in the the field of
rocket technology between the two countries, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said companies believed by the U.S. to have participated in
building rockets in Iran have been checked "in the most thorough
way."
</P>
<P>
He added that the joint construction of a nuclear power station
in Bushehr, Iran, was strictly supervised by the International
Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that despite the allegation, which was
aimed at preventing Russia from cooperating economically with
Iran, Russia will continue to trade with Iran. 
