<HEADLINE> Top-seeded Hoyer-Erik Larsen Quits from HK Open(Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Denmark's Olympic champion
Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen has quit for family reasons from the 1997
170,000 U.S. dollars Millennium Hong Kong Open Badminton
Championsh starting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The world number three and the men's singles top seed for the
five-day event will compete in the China Open set to open in
Shanghai, China in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
And his pull out did not quite bother Danish national coach
Henrik Lyngby.
</P>
<P>
"We're expecting for very good results here, even if Poul-Erik
Larsen is not here," he said.
</P>
<P>
He thought second seed Peter Christensen Gade "is probably one
of our strongest at the moment. Out goal is definately to win the
title here."
</P>
<P>
Lyngby picked up Indonesia's former world champion Joko
Suprianto, who is seeded ninth here, and his teammate Marieve
Mainaky from the field as the ones to watch at the Hong Kong event.
</P>
<P>
But he is happy with the team as a whole. "Even we are surpsied
that we have so many players in the world's top ten for the first
time in the history," he comented.
</P>
<P>
"As China brought here a very yong team, so we don't expect
them to take the gold medal this year," the Danish coach put
frankly.
</P>
<P>
"We had a fairly young team here and they all need to be
steeled through international tournaments," said Chinese captain
Ren Chunhui.
</P>
<P>
His idea was echoed by Chinese coach Yang Daiming.
</P>
<P>
"As our first-line players are preparing for the China Open,
the Hong Kong Open offered the best chance for the younger ones to
test their stregnth," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese duet Qian Hong annd Liu Lu, ranked fifth in the
world, are hot contenders for the women's doubles title, Yang
added.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei's defending men's singles champion Permandi Fung
said that his goal here was to "play to the final day." But his
latest shape put doubt on his expectation.
</P>
<P>
"I did not do well this year," he admitted. He could only
managed to the top eight before declining out of the race in the
Danish Open. He is now ranked 16th in the world.
</P>
<P>
The five-star event has drawn more than 100 players from 15
countries and regions including China, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Thailand, Denmark, South Korea, Japan and host Hong Kong which is
China's Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The competition program are men's and women's singles, doubles
and mixed doubles events.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Open is one of the 22 events worldwide on the
IBF-sectioned World Grand Prix series. Players who earn enough
points in the series are to be invited to the World Grand Prix
Finals in December in Jakarta, Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
