<HEADLINE> President Clinton Says U.S. Economy Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
stressed today that U.S. economy is strong, apparently to calm
nervous investors when the stock market is in a turmoil.
</P>
<P>
But he said it wouldn't be "prudent nor appropriate" to comment
on the market's hour by hour gyrations.
</P>
<P>
"Our economy is as strong and vibrant today as it has been in a
generation," Clinton said at a Chicago public school. "We have to
feel confident and continue our economic strategy."
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging global concerns over plunging financial markets,
Clinton said that "a lot of Americans are focused on the stock
market and it may be disappointing, but I think it neither prudent
nor appropriate for any president to comment on the hour-by-hour
or the day-by-day movements of the market."
</P>
<P>
"With unemployment and inflation at their lowest levels in two
decades and businesses and banks healthy and sound, with new jobs
being created every day, our economy is continuing to grow steady
and strong," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average resumed plunging at the
opening bell today, losing as much as 180 points in the first
minutes of trading, but by the Dow was up over 100 points the time
Clinton made the speech.
</P>
<P>
Since a 544-point drop in the Dow Jones Industrial average on
Monday, the largest in points but only the 12th biggest in
percentage terms, the U.S. government officials have sought to
reassure nervous investors about the fundamental soundness of the
U.S. economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
