<HEADLINE> Canada to Have Boom Year for Energy Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Western Canada's booming energy
industry is headed for even higher levels of drilling in 1998,
according to a new survey published today.
</P>
<P>
The survey estimates 16,300 oil and gas wells will be drilled
next year, up from this year's record of 14,700.
</P>
<P>
Sector revenues are expected to swell to 6.2 billion dollars
(4.5 billion USD), up from 5.1 billion dollars this year,
according to the survey compiled for the Petroleum Services
Association of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The industry is predicted to drill 9,061 oil wells, 3,957
natural gas wells, 2,782 dry wells and 500 service wells in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Drilling focused on natural gas is up only moderately at this
point, but activity could escalate late in the year, and into
1999, if plans to build new pipelines are approved, said
association president Roger Soucy.
</P>
<P>
It will be a challenge for the sector, which is already
struggling with equipment and staff shortages to keep up with
industry demand.
</P>
<P>
Soucy said that more drilling doesn't mean an increase in
overall production because of aging oilfields.
</P>
<P>
However, it allows the industry to maintain production at
current levels, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
