<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Wages, Benefits Up Moderately in 3rd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Wages and benefits paid to
American workers rose a moderate 0.8 percent in the third quarter,
U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it was another sign that U.S. inflation in
the labor market remains relatively contained.
</P>
<P>
The report said that July-September quarter increase in total
compensation included a 0.9 percent rise in wages and salaries
following a 0.8 percent increase the previous quarter. Wages and
salaries climbed by 3.5 percent over the 12 months ended in
September, the most in nearly six years.
</P>
<P>
Benefits rose by 0.4 percent in the third quarter, down from a
0.6 percent increase in the second quarter. They're up by 1.9
percent for the past year.
</P>
<P>
The report shows a slow upward creep in wages and benefits that
companies have so far managed to meet through improved
productivity.
</P>
<P>
The increase in total compensation followed an identical gain
in the previous quarter, according to the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
The rise was predicted by many U.S. economists and thus was
unlikely to have a major impact on the U.S. stock market which has
been reeling from a worldwide selling wave triggered by a crash in
the Hong Kong stock market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
