<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambians Lash at Attempted Military Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) --The attempted Military coup,
staged by Zambian army rebels this morning, was put down by armed
forces loyal to the government only two hours after it staged.
The abortive coup has evoked wide condemnation in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide speech on the television this afternoon,
Zambian President Chiluba condemned the aborted coup and vowed to
avoid possible bloodshed in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the coupists want to destabilize the country at the
expense of the interests of the Zambian people, adding that no
force against his government will succeed.
</P>
<P>
The president said that his government is determined to
continue the economic and political reforms in spite of strong
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Alec Chirwa, General Secretary of Zambia Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU), also condemned the failed coup, saying that it has
cast a "dark cloud" over all peace-loving citizens in the country
as people are not sure what would happen next.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU does not believe that military coups are the best way
to resolve problems in Zambia, said Chirwa.
</P>
<P>
Many residents interviewed this morning said that a military
rule can not be accepted in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the United States ambassador to the United
Nations, who was visiting Kenya on a six-nation African tour,
also condemned the coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
"We are always concerned about undemocratic, unconstitutional
overthrows of elected governments," said Richardson in response
to the coup before leaving Nairobi today.
</P>
<P>
In the Early morning, a group of soldiers from the army
besieged the State House where President Chiluba lives and took
the Mass Media Complex which houses the Zambian Broadcasting
Corporation, the Zambian Information Services and the Zambian
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
In a statement broadcast around six o'clock local time, the
coup leader Captain "Solo", who were identified later by army
sources as Captain Steven Mungu, claimed that the National
Redemption Council he represented had taken over the government
and demanded President Chiluba to resign.
</P>
<P>
He justified the military action by saying that the governance
by Chiluba's Movement for Multi-Democracy Movement is corrupted
and undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
About two hours later, the coupists were evicted from around
the State House by armed forces loyal to the government. However,
the government did not take control of the situation until
heavily-armed forces besieged the Mass Media Complex and arrested
most of the coupists including Captain "Solo". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Private University to Open in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 28 (Xinhua)-- More than 300 students are
sitting for the admission exams for a newly established private
university in the Somali capital among the anarchy and
lawlessness in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu University, situated in north of the capital, was
founded by a group of Somali professors who have long been
studying how they could revive the Somali universities which had
collapsed with the late regime early 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, unlike former universities run by the government,
this new university will charge the students with a fee of US
$300 for each student per academic year, according to the
administration of the university.
</P>
<P>
About 400 students are required to attend the first academic
year which will begin on November 8 after the on-going exams. The
students are required to obtain high secondary school diploma
with good conduct.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of the university Ali Hassan Mohamed said the
private university offers four year long high education and has
three faculties of law and sharia, education and arts.
</P>
<P>
In these faculties, Somali students will acquire full
knowledge of Islamic studies, sharia and international law,
history, languages, physics, biology and chemistry.
</P>
<P>
Lectures will be offered by 12 permanent local and foreign
professors together with other part time lecturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
