<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Junta Lifts Curfew Following Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has lifted the night curfew on the capital Freetown
following last Thursday's peace agreement it signed with west
African countries to return power to the ousted government within
six months.
</P>
<P>
The state radio announced on Monday that the midnight-to-6:00
a.m. curfew, put in force since the May 25 coup, had been lifted
with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was warmly welcomed by many Freetown
residents, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of residents who fled clashes between junta forces
and the west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG enforcing
sanctions against the country have been streaming back since the
signing of the agreement, it said.
</P>
<P>
The accord with the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) calls for a truce, disarmament, a broad-based government
under ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and amnesty for coup
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has won wide welcome among the international
community, and ECOWAS member countries in particular.
</P>
<P>
But Kabbah said on Monday he had not yet been briefed on the
accord signed in Conakry, capital of Guinea.
</P>
<P>
He said he would seek clarifications on why it would take
until April 22 next year for him to resume power.
</P>
<P>
He would seek assistance from the European Union to rebuild
his country, Kabbah said at a new conference earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
