<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports IGAD-Brokered Sudan Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to the U.N.
William Richardson said here today that the U.S. administration
supports Wednesday's Sudan peace talks brokered by the
Inter-Governmental Authority of Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when meeting Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi this morning, citing the demonstration of U.S. support as a
key reason behind his brief visit, the Kenyan News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Richardson arrived here on Monday and left before noon today.
He is on a six-African-nation tour which also include Democratic
Republic of Congo, Eritrea, Angola, Ethiopia and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will contribute 130,000 U.S. Dollars towards IGAD
initiative to end the Sudan civil war, Richardson told Moi, who
is chairman of IGAD, a regional forum comprising Sudan, Eritrea,
Uganda, Somalia, Kenya, Djibouti and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders of this organization (IGAD) deserve the world's
praise for establishing a negotiating framework that seeks to
advance the rights and interests of the Sudanese people," said
Richardson in a statement issued before talks with Moi.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is encouraged at that the countries of the Horn of
Africa have come together to create a peaceful solution to the
14-year conflicts that has devastated southern Sudan, according
to Richardson's statement.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan peace negotiations are to open here tomorrow
afternoon under the auspices of IGAD with an IGAD ministerial
meeting first.
</P>
<P>
Salve Kiir, Chief of Staff of Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA) will lead the rebel team and Foreign Minister Hussein abu
Saleh will head the Khartoum delegation in the talks.
</P>
<P>
The war in Sudan has claimed more than 1.3 million lives and
made tens of thousands displaced in the country since 1983 when
the SPLA rose to fight against Islamic-backed Khartoum power for
a secular state and more autonomy in the Christian-dominated
south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
