<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Federal Help to Upgrade Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today ordered the federal education officials to distribute
guidelines to school districts to upgrade school education in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton instructed the Education Department to help local
districts get better access to existing federal programs and
resources, such as charter schools or his "America Reads"
volunteer tutoring program, "to transform schools that are not
performing into world-class learning centers."
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Oscar Mayer Elementary School in Chicago,
Clinton praised reforms instituted by Chicago Mayor Richard Daley.
</P>
<P>
The mayor took control of the school system, abolished the
practice of promoting children for social reasons and required
that students meet academic standards in grades 3, 6, 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
"Ending social promotion does not put children down. It gives
us a chance to lift all children up," Clinton said. "When they
move from grade to grade, it means something. All of our children
can succeed, and they deserve a chance to do it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
