<HEADLINE> Official: Russia-Eastern Europe Arms Trade Has Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Russia holds that there is a
future for arms trade with former Warsaw Pact countries, the
Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister for Foreign Economic Relations and Trade
Vladimir Pakhomov was quoted as saying that "Interesting areas of
cooperation for trade in arms and related services with Poland,
Bulgaria, the Czech Republic and Slovakia have appeared."
</P>
<P>
Pakhomov said "Russia and many Eastern European countries have
signed new agreements on cooperation in arms trade."
</P>
<P>
He said he saw such links between Russia and Slovakia as
especially promising. Moscow and Bratislava "have recently
prepared a memorandum on Russian arms supplies to Slovakia through
the year 2000," the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Moscow will supply Bratislava with 140 million US
dollars worth of military equipment, including S-300 PMU
anti-aircraft system, in order to offset part of its debt," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also cooperate in the production of Yak-130
training planes powered with Slovakian engines, Pakhomov said. In
his opinion, "this plane has every chance of selling successfully
on foreign markets."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other former Warsaw Pact countries have chosen other
ways to upgrade their armed forces, which are different from the
case of Slovakia. However, Moscow is ready to work with these
countries as well, presuming that the economy holds out," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Also, "Russia expects to take part in different European
projects via its Eastern European partners," Pakhomov said. Within
the scope of such cooperation, Russia could hand over its latest
technology and borrow some technology from its partners at the
same time, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
