<HEADLINE> S. Africa, EU Could Reach Trade Accord in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations between
South Africa and the European Union (EU) on a comprehensive trade
and development agreement are on track and could be concluded by
mid-1998, the South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
An EU parliamentary delegation is in South Africa for talks
about the trade pact with various South African government
departments, non-governmental organizations and politicians.
</P>
<P>
They briefed South African National Assembly's foreign
affairs, trade and industry, and agricultural committees on
progress made toward an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Head of the delegation, Gerald Collins of Ireland, said the
talks have been going on for 27 months, but that negotiations of
such a nature usually take 36 months.
</P>
<P>
He said major difficulties lie in fisheries and agricultural
products. However, he said, none of the problems appeared
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is reluctant to include fisheries into the accord
and complained about EU protectionism in agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Another member of the EU delegation, Caroline Jackson of
Britain, told the committees that some European countries, such
as Spain, Portugal and Greece, are especially opposed to open
trade, as they produce similar agricultural products to South
Africa, such as fruit, wine and spirits.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and the EU are also involved in negotiations
about South Africa's accession to the Lome Convention, through
which the EU grants aid to 70 African, Caribbean and Pacific
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU is South Africa's largest trading partner and source of
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
