<HEADLINE> Liberia, Libya Establish Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Liberia has established
diplomatic relations with Libya, and appointed its ambassador to
Tripoli, it is reported today.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted a government communique as
saying that Moses Blah, a former commander of President Charles
Taylor's defunct National Patriotic Front militia, would serve as
Liberia's ambassador to Tripoli as well as Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Liberia and Libya had trade relations before Taylor launched
the civil war in 1989, but there has been no diplomatic relations
for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
Blah's appointment comes less than a month after Liberia and
Libya signed a joint communique in Tripoli, calling for increased
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a Libyan delegation arrived in
Monrovia, capital of Liberia, last month to discuss the opening
of a Libyan people's bureau (embassy).
</P>
<P>
The delegation comprised Rajab Fartas, senior member of the
Libyan People's Congress (parliament), Fadel Saity, Libyan
ambassador-designate to Liberia, and Ashur Moushai, adviser on
international relations to Libyan leader Col. M. Gaddafi.
</P>
<P>
Taylor's militia group, which ignited the rebellion in
Liberia, received military training in Libya in 1988 before
attacking Liberia from neighboring Cote d'Ivoire on Christmas Eve
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of people were killed in the seven-year
bloody civil war, with more others fleeing the country as
refugees or displaced.
</P>
<P>
Taylor finally achieved his goal and became the Liberian
president after winning the elections in July this year.
</P>
<P>
He paid a visit to Libya as president of Liberia late last
month to strengthen bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Taylor recently signed the country's
first human rights bill, vowing to take the lead in fighting
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides for a human rights commission to be
appointed by the government, but the neutrality and independence
of the commission was questioned by human rights groups in the
capital Monrovia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
