<HEADLINE> Blockade on S. Leone to Continue Despite Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The blockade on Sierra Leone is
to continue despite the peace accord signed between the military
junta and west African countries, the Nigerian defense
headquarters announced today.
</P>
<P>
The economic sanctions against the junta was still on although
the junta had agreed to quit in six months, said Col. Godwin
Ugbo, acting director of defense information.
</P>
<P>
West African countries and the junta signed a peace agreement
last Thursday in Conakry, capital of Guinea, which set April 22
next year as the date to hand over to elected President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah was ousted in the May 25 coup, which invited sanctions
imposed by both its west African neighbors and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) led by Nigerian
troops has been mandated to enforce the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
According to Ugbo, ECOMOG would continue to prevent supply of
arms and ammunition to the military authorities in Sierra Leone
as a way of ensuring a faster resolution of the crisis triggered
off by the coup.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement also requires a cease-fire between the
junta and ECOMOG troops, disarmament of combatants in that
country, an all-embracing government under Kabbah and amnesty for
coup leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
