<HEADLINE> Somalia's Aideed Promises Dialogue with Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A leading Somali faction leader
reaffirmed his commitment today to holding dialogues with rival
leaders to advance the country's reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
The Somali National Alliance, the most powerful Somali faction,
was ready to open dialogue with all who follow democratic courses,
its leader Hussein Farah Aideed told reporters here after meeting
with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, who arrived here Monday, may hold talks with his
arch-rival Ali Mahdi Mohamed, leader of the Somali Salvation
Alliance, in Cairo Wednesday on ways to end their long-running
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Egypt mediated for months between Aideed and Mahdi, who signed
a reconciliation agreement in Cairo on May 29 on holding talks. At
least three agreements were signed between them in the aftermath
but none was carried out.
</P>
<P>
Aideed praised Egypt's role in Somalia's reconciliation process
within the context of the Arab and African efforts exerted to
unify Somali ranks.
</P>
<P>
He discussed with Moussa the Somali national unity conference,
organized by the National Salvation Council, which is due to be
held next month in the Somali town of Bosaso, south of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, who is seen as the key to a lasting peace in Somalia,
has refused to join the National Salvation Council, which was
formed by 26 faction leaders in January, and has yet to agree to
attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
Since the ouster of the late dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in
1991, Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected by
faction leaders, who continued to fight to expand their turfs
despite a number of peace conferences.
</P>
<P>
The factional fighting, combined with a 1992 famine, has
claimed about 350,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
