<HEADLINE> Mozambique Denounces Coup Bid in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Ministry of
Foreign Affairs and Cooperation today issued a press communique
denouncing the coup in Zambia in an attempt to overthrow the
government of President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government, said the statement, denounced the
failed coup aimed at ousting the democratically-elected
government in Zambia, and congratulated the Zambian government on
its immediate restoration of law and order in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Mozambican government strongly condemns the disgusting
event which was aimed at sabotaging the stability and democratic
atmosphere in Zambia and other member states of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC)," the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated Mozambique's support and friendship toward the
lawful authorities of the brotherly Zambia Republic.
</P>
<P>
Some Zambian soldiers launched a military coup early this
morning. But a few hours later, President F. Chiluba announced
on state radio that the coup had been smashed and that he has
taken complete control of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old Chiluba was re-elected in November 1996 as
president of Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
