<HEADLINE> Campaign Bill Blocks Action on Highway Legislation Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- For the fourth time in two
weeks, Democrats today blocked action on a highway building bill
to pressure Republicans into scheduling full debate and action on
a campaign finance overhaul measure in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
The vote was 52-48, eight votes short of the 60 needed to end
the Democratic filibuster of the 145 billion-dollar bill. All
votes to end the filibuster were cast by Republicans, while three
Republicans joined the 45 Democrats in voting against it.
</P>
<P>
Democrats have said they will block virtually all legislation
not related to spending for fiscal 1998, which began October 1.
Congress has finished work on seven of the 13 appropriations
bills, and President Bill Clinton has signed six of them into law.
</P>
<P>
Majority Leader Trent Lott, Republican from Mississippi, has
said he would pull the six-year highway bill off the floor if he
failed to overcome the Democratic filibuster today.
</P>
<P>
Senator Rod Grams, a Republican, called the delaying action a
politically motivated attempt to halt crucial legislation.
</P>
<P>
"It's ironic that senators proclaiming to support labor issues
would now thumb their noses at the same hard-working Americans who
feed and clothe their families through the salaries they earn
working on transportation projects," Grams said in a speech today
before the vote.
</P>
<P>
Minority Leader Thomas Daschle, in a speech after the vote,
urged Republican leaders to reach agreement on a date for full
debate of campaign finance legislation and then move to
consideration of the full six-year highway bill.
</P>
<P>
The campaign finance bill that Democrats support -- a
bipartisan measure sponsored by Senators John McCain, a
Republican, and Russell Feingold, a Democrat -- was debated for
several days on the Senate floor earlier this month before being
blocked by a Republican filibuster.
</P>
<P>
Lott allowed only one amendment -- to require unions to get
permission from each member before spending any dues for political
purposes. Democrats blocked that with a filibuster of their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
