<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambian Coup Meets with Continental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian coup, which
lasted no more than five hours before it was clamped down by the
government troops today, has been receiving condemnations from
the African society.
</P>
<P>
Of all countries and organizations that stood against the
abortive coup, member states of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) have expressed strongest disapproval of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
South Africa took the lead in denouncing the military coup
soon after it happened in the early morning.
</P>
<P>
"The whole world will condemn what is happening in Zambia
today," Premier Tokyo Sexwale of Gauteng Province, South Africa,
told reporters hours before the mutiny was put down by troops
loyal to Zambian President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Describing the coup as "bad news for this continent, Sexwale
said, "the era of guns and tanks rolling out of the camps against
civilians has got to come to an end in Africa."
</P>
<P>
Following Sexwale's remarks, South Africa's ruling African
National Congress (ANC) issued a statement, saying it
"unequivocally condemns attempts by a clique of military officers
to use unconstitutional means to remove from office the
democratically-elected government of Zambia".
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that "Africa can no longer tolerate
undemocratic, dictatorial and militaristic regimes being imposed
upon the will of the majority of the people any where on the
continent."
</P>
<P>
It said whatever political problems may exist, such problems
should be resolved through political and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
While the South African government was condemning the foiled
coup, acting President Thabo Mbeki had been in touch with leaders
in the southern African region to discuss the matter, acting
South African foreign minister Valli Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to South African President Nelson Mandela, Mbeki
had contacted with President F. Chiluba of Zambia and SADC
Chairman Robert Mugabe, Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said South Africa would take the opportunity to reaffirm
the commitment of the SADC region to act in defense of democracy
and the protection of human rights, as well as against the
seizure of power through the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Sharing South Africa's view point, Zimbabwe today also voiced
its support to the legal government headed by President Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Deputy Foreign Minister Nicholas Goche said African
countries needed to uphold the stance of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) to exercise democracy when it came to change
governments.
</P>
<P>
"Change of government should be done through the ballot box,"
Goche told reporters at the one-day meeting of the Foreign
Affairs Sub-committee of the Zimbabwe-South Africa Joint
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The OAU has always been concerned about undemocratic
overthrows of elected governments. In its annual meeting in
Harare, Zimbabwe early this year, the OAU adopted a resolution
calling on all the African countries not to recognize any
political regime which takes state power by force.
</P>
<P>
The OAU also appealed to all political parties in Africa to
resolve their problems through peaceful means so as to create
stability for economic development in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, SADC executive secretary, said the Zambian coup
has set back the progress of democracy in Africa, particularly in
southern Africa, noting "it will cast a shadow of doubt on the
future political stability of our region."
</P>
<P>
Mbuende stressed that SADC member states must try their best
to prevent such event from happening again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
