<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Minister Visits Egypt Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov will begin his visit to Egypt Wednesday to discuss
regional and bilateral issues, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Russian minister's visit is of special importance
considering the peace crisis in the Middle East, Mohamed Fathi al
Shazli, assistant foreign minister told the Middle East News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is expected to hold talks with his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa on the latest developments in the peace
process, current situations in Iraq and Libya, and ways to enhance
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the last leg of Primakov week-long Mideast tour which
has taken him to Lebanon, Syria, Israel, the Palestinian self-rule
areas and Jordan. The trip was aimed to boost Russia's profile as
a co-sponsor of the peace process and help revive Arab-Israeli
talks on all tracks.
</P>
<P>
Al Shazli said the present impasse in the peace march requires
the international community, mainly Moscow, to push forward
"whether by words, deeds or by acts."
</P>
<P>
Russia, alongside with the U.S., co-sponsored the Madrid
conference in 1991 to set the Middle East peace wheel going.
However, its inactivity over the past few years left the
U.S. dominated the scene in brokering Arab-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's Cairo trip was agreed upon by the two countries'
presidents, Boris Yeltsin and Hosni Mubarak, during the latter's
visit to Moscow last month, al Shazli said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov and Moussa will also follow up the steps to carry out
agreements and resolutions recently adopted by the joint committee
of the two countries to broaden cooperation as well as bilateral
relation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
