<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges NATO to Stop Greek-Russian Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has sent a letter to
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to protest against
the Greek-Russian alliance, a senior military official confirmed
here today.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Chief of General Staff Cevik Bir told the
press that the letter was aimed at warning NATO over the
increasing Greek-Russian threat to Turkey's security, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Sabah reported today that Ismail Hakki Karadayi,
the chief of general staff of Turkish Armed Forces, had written
to his NATO counterparts to voice Ankara's concern over the
Greek-Russian alliance against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Karadayi warned that Greece, a NATO member, is
now joining hands with Russia to threaten the state security of
Turkey, which is also a member country of NATO.
</P>
<P>
"We demand you take measures against these grave developments
that could lead to the collapse of the NATO's southern flank,"
he said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Turkish relations have become even worse since the
Cypriot government made it clear that it would not give up its
plan to buy anti-aircraft S-300 missiles from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly threatened that it would use force to
destroy all the missiles if they are finally deployed in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Russia, however, warned earlier that Moscow will see it as a
declaration of war against the Russian Federation if Turkey
attacks vesseles shipping the missiles to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkish General Staff has not received any response from NATO
and its member states so far, Bir said.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, two traditionally rival countries, have
long been at odds over a number of issues, including the mineral
resources of the Agean, airspace division as well as the
settlement of the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
