<HEADLINE> Mercedes to Modify New Compact Car After Freak Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- German Daimler-Benz said today its
subsidiary Mercedes would upgrade its newly introduced A-Class
autos with new tires and electronics in response to reports that
the car has tipped over in tests.
</P>
<P>
The Stuttgart-based parent company said some 3,000 of the new
Mercedes compacts, which went on sale just a few days ago, have
already been delivered. They will be recalled and refitted with
new tires and an electronic stability program.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference called to discuss the A-Class's safety,
Daimler-Benz car division chief Juergen Hubbert said the tires
fitted to the A-Class were too soft and could make the car
unstable during quick evasive turns.
</P>
<P>
The A-Class became the object of intense scrutiny about its
safety after Swedish motoring magazine Teknikens Varld flipped one
of the cars during tests, injuring the driver.
</P>
<P>
The car rolled over when the driver made a sharp left turn
while traveling at a speed of 60 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
Daimler said the refitting would cost 57.5 million U.S. dollars
a year, but it would not raise the price of the car, which sells
for around 30,000 German marks (17,100 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The A-class is a five-door hatchback designed to compete with
the best selling Volkswagen Golf. It is a new product for Mercedes
which has traditionally built larger saloons and sports models.
</P>
<P>
The company said the A-class models have been tested
extensively without incident. Orders for the new car extend into
the middle of next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
