<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC States Halve Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) countries have cut in half their budget deficits between
1993 and 1996, said a report released by the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The budget shortfall in the six-member alliance was slashed
from around 20.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1993 to 10.9 billion
dollars last year, said the report obtained here today.
</P>
<P>
It attributes this to a pick-up in oil prices which rebounded
from 16 dollars per barrel in 1995 to 20.5 dollars a barrel in
1996. The improvement has enabled the GCC states to earn a 13-year
high of 83 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that a sharp reduction in most of the
GCC states' expenditures also helped them to narrow their budget
gap.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states which include Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait,
Bahrain, Qatar and Oman were forced to trim their spending due to
weak oil prices before 1996.
</P>
<P>
The spending cuts were offset by stronger private sector
involvement in the domestic economies and this boosted their
combined Gross Domestic Product to 238 billion dollars in 1996
from around 203 billion dollars in 1992, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The international reserves of the GCC are also recovering,
standing at 24.6 billion dollars at the end of June. This
compares with around 19 billion dollars in 1992, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Oil-reliant GCC states have been reeling under fluctuating
crude prices and huge payments for a U.S.-led multinational
coalition which evicted Iraq from Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Their budgets suffered from a record deficit of nearly 63
billion dollars in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, Nepali Private Sectors Urged to Promote Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The private sectors of
Pakistan and Nepal should endeavor to bridge the communication gap
for promoting bilateral trade, Speaker of the Nepalese House of
Representatives Ram Chandler said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry in
Lahore in northeast Pakistan, Chandler, head of a nine-member
Nepalese parliamentary delegation, called upon the local business
community to take initiative for strong and long-term business
relations with Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Chandler is in Pakistan to attend the second conference of the
Association of Speakers and Parliamentarians of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation, which was held in Islamabad
from October 26 to 28.
</P>
<P>
Chandler said he would apprise the Nepalese businessmen of the
conducive investment climate with lucrative incentives in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said commerce chambers of both countries would work out
practical proposals for joint ventures in the commercial and
industrial sectors.  
</P>
