<HEADLINE> HK Ambitious in Building Infrastructure Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong secretary for
transport today outlined an ambitious government plan for building
infrastructure projects for the next century.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Ng told the Provisional Legislative Council here that
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government
would spend more than 140 billion HK dollars (18 billion U.S.
dollars) to build railways and roads in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
He said three rail projects are in the pipeline and they
include the West Rail, the Tseung Kwan O Extension and the Ma On
Shan to Tai Wai Extension. Construction of the first two railroads
is expected to start next year and will be completed in 2002 and
2003.
</P>
<P>
The official also listed six new road projects and four old
roads that need improvement.
</P>
<P>
In working out the road-building plan, the government has taken
into account housing development, the increase in population and
the closer links with the inland areas of China, he said. 
</P>
