<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Stocks Rise, Won Tumbles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Seoul bourse
rose 2.29 percent today to regain the lost 500-point level, but the
South Korean won fell further against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The market started off with a plunge of 8 points, continuing
its decline from the previous four days. Immediately after the
opening, however, the overnight strong rebound on Wall Street, as
well as the news of the recovery of the Hang Seng Index, buoyed
investors' sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark South Korea Stock Price Index (KOSPI) rose 11.36
points to close at 506.65.
</P>
<P>
However, market observers cautioned that the local market is
extremely sensitive to outside factors, including moves of the
global markets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, despite renewed governmental resolve for "direct"
intervention, the South Korean won fell today to their daily limit
lows against the dollar for the second consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
The won opened at 956.00 won to the greenback and fell to an
allowable low of 964.00 won in just 40 minutes of trading,
bringing all transaction to a near halt amid no sell orders for
dollars, currency dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Since December 1995, the Central Bank of Korea has allowed the
won to move within a daily range of plus or minus 2.5 percent from
the previous day's closing. The South Korean currency closed at
957.60 won per dollar Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean won has depreciated about 13 percent from
December 31, 1996 when it was posted at 844.20 won to U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by the won's sharp plunge against the U.S. dollar in
two days, market participants here raised doubt over whether the
monetary authorities have given up intervening in the
domestic foreign-exchange market to defend the won.
</P>
<P>
A central bank official, however, strongly refuted such an
allegation, saying that the central bank would continue to step in
to the market to keep the won-dollar parity rate at a proper level.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers cautiously warned that the won would fall below
the 1,000-won level to the dollar in a few days, not by the end of
this year, if the government leaves the current situation
untouched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Hong Kong Stock Market Rebounds, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong stock market
rallied today after an amazing recovery in Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index rocketed 1,705 points, or 18.8 percent
today, recouping all the devastating losses on Tuesday. The
rebound, the biggest single-day gain both in terms of points and
percentage, pushed the blue-chip index up to 10,765 points. Stock
prices plummeted more than 1,400 points Tuesday, the heaviest
point loss in history.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise today showed that the confidence of investors
was picking up, but the market will still be volatile in the short
run, said a securities analyst. In the last few days, many listed
companies purchased their own shares as the prices had fallen to
the bottom.
</P>
<P>
"Confidence is the most decisive factor that will influence the
direction of the stock market in the next few weeks," Brian
Parker, head of Hong Kong Research of Credit Lyonnais Securities
Asia, told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Parker said positive signs have now emerged as Wall Street
rebounded, Hong Kong's primary interest rates, once jacked up to
record levels, began to scale down and the market has never been
cheaper to offer opportunities for bargain hunting.
</P>
<P>
He refused to predict when the market is going to bottom out,
but estimated that it would swing around the fair level of 12,000
points.
</P>
<P>
The recent severe downturn in the Hong Kong stock market was
triggered by international speculators, who wanted to flush
investors out of the market, which reached its peak of above
16,000 points in early August, said Russell Napier, regional
strategist of Credit Lyonnais Securities Asia.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some international funds attacked the Hong
Kong currency's peg to the greenback and in turn interest rates in
 Hong Kong were forced up to a record high. The eventual result
was that stock investors became panic and sold off shares to
throw the market into a free fall.
</P>
<P>
However, Napier maintained an optimistic outlook for the Hong
Kong market. Hong Kong remains a very profitable place to do
business despite its high costs and China plays a unique role in
boosting Hong Kong's competitiveness, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
