<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Industrialists Facing New Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong needs to expand
into higher value-added, technology-intensive activities in order
to stay ahead of its competitors, a high-ranking official of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) said here today.
</P>
<P>
K C Kwong, HKSAR secretary for treasury, told a group of local
young industrialists that Hong Kong's competitive edge lies in its
position as the gateway to China.
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned: "Hong Kong will not be making the best use of
our position as an SAR of China if we merely continue to rely only
on the supply of relatively cheap land and labor in the mainland."
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, Hong Kong businessmen have moved on
a large scale their manufacturing operations to southern China and
later to the inland parts of the country to take advantage of the
lower costs of land and labor there.
</P>
<P>
Now Hong Kong manufacturers employ more than 7 million workers
in the inland areas while Hong Kong has become a service center
that concentrates on product design, marketing, financing,
insurance and shipping. The result is a winning formula that has
strengthened Hong Kong's competitiveness, Kwong noted.
</P>
<P>
He urged Hong Kong's young industrialists to continue to
develop and adopt new technology, tap high value-added fields and
make full use of the knowledge and expertise from China's inland
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
