<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea, EU Agree on Talks on Recognition of Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the European
Union (EU) agreed today to negotiate an agreement on mutual
recognition of industrial standards.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was outlined during the 13th South Korea-EU
ministrial meeting between the two delegations, which were
respectively led by South Korean Foreign Minister Yoo Chong-ha and
Leon Brittan, EU's vice president and commissioner for external
relations, said ministry spokesman Lee Kyu-hyung.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to hold seminars in Seoul and Brussels to
explain the two markets' recognition systems to members of their
business communities, said Lee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they also agreed to set up a program to coordinate
exchange visits of businessmen and launch a separate working-level
meeting on industrial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a move to promote mutual trade and investment, the EU
promised to allow South Korean companies to use BC-net, the
information network of small- and medium-sized firms of the EU,
beginning in 1998, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
The EU agreed to end sometime soon the anti-dumping tariffs on
South Korean-made DRAM chips, video tapes and color TV units, and
also to import Samgyetang, a traditional Korean-style chicken soup
with Ginseng and other herbs, he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU urged South Korea to ease inspections on imported
cosmetics, simplify quarantine and customs procedures and further
open its auto market to foreign auto makers.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean side said Seoul has made efforts to facilitate
foreign access to its auto market, explaining that a recent
decrease in foreign car sales in South Korea was a result of the
country's economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation reaffirmed EU's support for four-way talks on
a permanent peace on the Korean Peninsula, promising that the EU,
which joined the Korean Peninsula Energy Development Organization
(KEDO) earlier this year, would continue to play an active role to
help maintain peace and stability on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
During the annual ministerial meeting, the two sides agreed to
hold regular policy dialogues on major international issues and to
strengthen cooperation in politics, the economy and security, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, Brittan and South Korean Information and
Communication Minister Kang Bong-kyun signed an agreement on
opening their communications equipment procurement markets to each
other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
