<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- A day before getting down to the serious diplomatic work
of his first state visit to Washington, President Jiang Zemin of
China wrapped himself in the culture of Colonial Williamsburg,
where the way of life of 18th century America is recreated in
traditional architecture, old-fashioned dress and modern tourism.
</P>
<P>
-- Main street rode in to rescue Wall street as America's
amateur investors rushed to buy stocks, halting the global
financial free fall that began last week. The Dow Jones
industrial average soared 4.7 percent, the greatest gain in more
than a decade and the sixth-largest ever.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin began
the first U.S.-Sino summit in eight years on an informal note
last night, huddling in the White House for almost two hours in
what administration officials described as a broad and
philosophical conversation. Both presidents endorsed a permanent
"hot line" between the two capitals.
</P>
<P>
-- Major stock markets in Europe and Latin America were given a
boost by Wall Street's record-setting gains on Tuesday, and the
volatile Asian markets rebounded with strong rallies. In Hong Kong
the key Hang Seng index shot up dramatically in the morning
session on Wednesday, climbing more than 16 percent, after losing
nearly 14 percent the day before.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- In a sweeping reaffirmation of their love affair with
stocks, investors on Tuesday besieged Wall Street with buy
orders, smashing records for the single-biggest point gain in
the Dow Jones industrial average and the biggest trading day on
the New York Stock Exchange. This sent important signals about
investor confidence in the U.S. economy, the resilience of the
seven-year-old bull market and the ability of financial
industry in handle sudden shifts in sentiment and huge volumes
of trading. 
</P>
