<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eco-Tourism Urged to Be Highlighted in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Tourism and Wildlife
Minister Protas Momanyi today called on African governments and
world experts to make efforts together to boost eco-tourism in
the whole Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The new approach and direction for tourism in general are
steered by the growing interest in eco-tourism," Momanyi noted at
the ongoing eco-tourism international conference, which, he said,
is the first-ever on the continent.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Kenyan government and all stake-holders in
the industry to "work in unity towards a commercial environment
which allows eco-tourism to be entrenched as a tourism business
norm" in the country.
</P>
<P>
"This new policy direction fosters bio-diversity conservation
through partnerships among local, national and international
interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the conference makes a remarked contribution to
Africa's eco-tourism agenda by bringing together world experts to
exchange ideas and experiences in the field.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has become the largest civil industry in the world and
will continue to swell up with nature-based eco-tourism,
participants noted at the conference which opened here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Eco-tourism, defined by the Eco-tourism Society as
"responsible travel to natural areas that conserves the
environment and sustains the well-being of local people," was
first popularized in Latin America and then rooted in Africa in
1970s.
</P>
<P>
The eco-tourism experience can be dated from nature tourism
which has flourished in the national parks of the Untied States
for over 100 years.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays eco-tourism, which focuses on the industry's quality
instead of quantity and try to have local communities benefited
from relevant natural resources, is representing the main trend
of future world travel market, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, with the theme as "Eco-tourism -- Charting the
Way Forward," was focused on how to draft eco-tourism principles
and improve eco-tourism operation on the continent in the next
century and global and regional case studies on successful
eco-tourism models.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the conference was an exhibition of
community-based tourism activities, showcasing the unique
heritage, handicrafts and tourism development efforts of Kenya's
40-plus diverse cultures.
</P>
<P>
More than 260 delegates from the U.S., Britain, South Africa,
Mexico, Brazil, Belize, Tanzania, Swaziland, Uganda, Australia,
Botswana, Namibia, Mozambique, Malawi, Zimbabwe and other
countries attended the meeting, which is to end on November 3.
</P>
<P>
World tourism hit a record high to 1996 with 593 million
international tourist arrivals, up 4.6 percent from the previous
year, according to the latest data from the World Tourism
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
