<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Returned Students Welcomed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- A delegation sponsored by
Jiangsu Province's Personnel Department will travel to the United
States and Germany to offer jobs to Chinese students.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, consisting of representatives from provincial
personnel departments, universities and enterprises will sponsor
recruiting activities in Los Angeles, New York, Washington,
Berlin and Munich from the end of October through November.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Guoxi, head of the delegation, noted that a recent survey
of 70 major enterprises, universities and scientific research
institutes revealed that more than 800 returned students will be
needed to fill job vacancies in the province.
</P>
<P>
The majority of jobs will be in five major sectors --
electronic technology, computers, materials engineering,
pharmacology, and industrial and commercial management.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, a rapidly developing province, has introduced a
series of preferential policies encouraging students to return to
China.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,597 of 10,000 Jiangsu students studying abroad have
returned to work in their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has sent about 270,000 students
abroad, with more than 90,000 having already returned to China
after completing their studies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uzbek GDP Increase Nearly 5% in January-September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Uzbekistan's gross
domestic product in the first nine months was up 4.9 percent
compared with the same period of last year, the Interfax news
agency reported today from Tashkent, capital of Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
It said the figure was announced at a session of the
Cabinet last Tuesday which was chaired by Prime Minister Utkir
Sultanov.
</P>
<P>
Gross industrial production during the first nine months
of 1997 rose 6.3 percent compared with the same period of 1996.
The increase in agricultural output totalled 12.7 percent. Trade
turnover grew 10.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a government spokesman, the budget deficit
did not exceed the existing limits and was 3 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
However, Deputy Prime Minister Bakhtiyer Sultanov, the
finance and foreign trade ministers, and the Central Bank's
chairman noted at the session that many enterprises remained
debtors despite some decrease in the total volumes of accounts
payable and receivable to the budget.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the report said, considerable debts are
owed by fuel, energy, chemical, metallurgical and agricultural
enterprises, companies in the sphere of services, transport and
communications.
</P>
<P>
The number of unprofitable enterprises in the country has
not declined and totals 230, the government said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
