<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Time to Wake Asia to Threat of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- An HIV/AIDS epidemic can be
possibly averted in Asia, the region of emerging economic tigers
and populous countries, only if it wakes up in time and
intensifies its campaign against the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
This is an opinion shared by many medical practitioners, AIDS
activists and researchers during the five-day Fourth International
Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacific, which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
And AIDS (acquired immuno-deficiency syndrome) is caused by the
human immuno-deficiency virus (HIV) and the late-stage HIV
infection, characterized by a severely weakened immune system.
</P>
<P>
Although HIV/AIDS is "traveling faster than ever" in Asia, hope
still exists for Asia to tame it since the dreaded disease is
still at an early stage in most Asian countries and an earlier
expected upsurge in infections has not yet occurred, they said.
</P>
<P>
During the last three years, the estimated HIV infections in
the region have doubled to between 5 million to 7 million,
according to the latest data from the U.N. Joint Program Against
AIDS (UNAIDS).
</P>
<P>
Asia is widely seen to be the next "flash point" for HIV/AIDS
in the coming years mainly due to its large populations, with the
total number of HIV infections expected to double again by the end
of this century, if no immediate actions are taken against the
virus.
</P>
<P>
But Perter Piot, executive director of UNAIDS, said that
considering the current low HIV incidence, the present time is
opportune for the region to take actions in averting what could
develop into a situation as serious as that in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"This is the grim face of AIDS that Africa had little chance to
prevent and one that Asia and the Pacific can still avert if the
region wakes up in time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 22.6 million people living with HIV and AIDS around the
world, 14 million are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
If a major HIV/AIDS epidemic strikes Asia, the region's current
economic revitalization drive will be jeopardized and prospects of
its future prosperity dimmed, delegates warned.
</P>
<P>
"The AIDS epidemic is the enemy of Asian economic promise. It
threatens in a material way the progress that Asia has made over
the past several decades," said Peter Sullivan, vice president of
the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
"It imposes huge economic costs on societies, families and
individuals and endangers the economic development of Asian
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Piot noted that apart from agony to families and individuals,
the deadly pandemic can slow down the economy by bringing about
huge direct medical costs, labor and market losses and increasing
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Taking Cambodia and Indonesia for instance, Piot said most
Asian countries could not afford to the high costs of an AIDS
epidemic in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said Cambodia, one of the poor countries in the world, could
lose 2.8 billion U.S. dollars if it could not prevent infections
of a projected 200,000 toward the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Delegates also agreed that increased political commitment,
enhanced regional cooperation and intensified prevention campaign
are the key for the region to combating HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Despite small victories in some countries such as Thailand and
the Philippines in curbing the spread of HIV/AIDS, Piot said every
government should shatter complacency, bring AIDS to national
consciousness and put the anti-AIDS campaign on its political
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Delegates also urged policy makers to spend more on AIDS
prevention, and boldly push regional anti-AIDS cooperation since
AIDS is a cross-border issue.
</P>
<P>
"Ultimately, Asia can meet the AIDS challenge if it uses
existing knowledge, existing tools and best practices," Piot
predicted. But he warned, "Not to take full advantage of all that
would be a tragedy of historic proportions for Asia's billions."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gambia Lifts Ban on Cigarette Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 29 (Xinhua)-- Parliament in the west African
state of Gambia has passed a law lifting a ban on cigarette
advertising in order to boost state revenues.
</P>
<P>
Finance and Economy Minister Dominic Mendy told reporters that
parliament's vote on Tuesday night had also cleared the way for
cigarette firms to sponsor sporting events in Gambia, said a
report reaching here from Banjul, capital of Gambia.
</P>
<P>
Cigarette advertising has been banned in the country since
1985. The bill was passed after heated debate in the assemby. All
33 ruling party deputies voted for while eight opposition
lawmakers voted against. 
</P>
</TEXT>
