<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sewage Handling Plants to Be Built in Three Gorges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, the newest
municipality in China, will invest heavily to protect the local
environment by building more plants to handle polluted water,
according to a senior local government official.
</P>
<P>
The municipality plans to invest 4 billion yuan in sewage
disposal projects in the coming five years, so as to dispel fears
that the ongoing Three Gorges Dam Project will further contaminate
the environment.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Deputy Mayor Gan Yuping said
that the project will use local resources as well as foreign
funds, including World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Substantial measures include building large facilities to
handle the domestic sewage and control the industrial
pollution. All local enterprises in Chongqing will be required to
reach the standards on sewage discharge by 2002, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
"Chongqing is going to clean the branches of the Yangtze River
to ensure the water quality," Gan said.
</P>
<P>
The environment protection plans in the Three Gorges area have
gained support from the central government, which has decided to
reinforce the construction of the shelter-forests on the upper and
middle reaches of the Yangtze River to conserve water and prevent
soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
"The sewage handling capacity in the whole Three Gorges area
is expected to reach one million tons per day in a few years,"
deputy-director of the Yangtze River Three Gorges Construction
Committee Guo Shuyan told Xinhua
</P>
<P>
"Chinese-made equipment will be mainly used in these
water-handling projects, but key equipment will be imported. This
offers a good opportunity for the foreign manufacturers," he added.
</P>
<P>
China is building the country's largest hydro-power project in
the Three Gorges area in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River to
control floods, generate electricity, and facilitate shipping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
