<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Not Ready for Washington Peace Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy has to delay his travel to the United States
until next week because today's Israeli inner Cabinet meeting
failed to reach guidelines for future negotiations with
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The abortive Cabinet meeting, that is expected to continue
discussions next week, ruled out the possibility of a meeting to
be held at the end of the month between Levy and Palestinian
deputy leader Mamoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Levy has said that only after the parameters for concessions
that Israel is expected to make and the commitments to be
undertaken by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) are defined
by the Cabinet, he will be able to leave for Washington.
</P>
<P>
The local media disclosed the meeting between Levy and Abbas
will not be feasible until late November or early December.
</P>
<P>
This is because U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
scheduled to attend the World Economic Forum's Middle East and
North Africa economic conference due to open in Qatar on November
16 and can not host Israeli-Palestinian negotiations in the
mid-November.
</P>
<P>
Levy conferred with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Monday
on three main issues which he wants specific instructions: a
"time-out" on settlement activity; further redeployment of Israeli
troops in the West Bank and preparations for the final status
talks.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian side, PNA President Yasser Arafat said
Monday that the PNA withheld a decision about whether to attend
next week's planned talks in Washington until Israel decides.
</P>
<P>
"We have to wait for the final resolution from the Israeli side
to decide if we will go to this meeting or not," Arafat
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Universities to Get Sun Microsystems Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Ten of China's universities
will benefit from the cooperation between the State Education
Commission of China (SEC) and Sun Microsystems, Inc. of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding signed today in
Beijing on behalf of the universities, Sun Microsystems will
supply several million U.S. dollars worth of computer-related
training, installation and maintenance services to the 10 schools,
including Beijing and Tsinghua universities.
</P>
<P>
Sun Microsystems, one of the top U.S. computer firms based in
California, is the provider of the Internet platform for CERNET
(China Education and Research Network).
</P>
<P>
The memorandum stipulates that within three years Sun
Microsystems will donate 110 units of computer hardware, such as
the highly advanced Sun (TM) workstations.
</P>
<P>
The donation also includes Java software technology and the
establishment of authorized Java training centers which will
enable students to learn computer skills that can be used for
accessing the Internet for educational and business purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
