<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan: Dialog With Egypt Key to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 29 (Xinhua) -- A Sudanese minister today
stressed the need of dialog with Cairo to solve Egyptian-Sudanese
problems and improve bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Mustafa Othman
Ismail made the remark following talks between Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and visiting Sudanese First Vice President el-Zubeir
Mohammad Salih.
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak has a marked understanding of Sudan's
issues...Our relationship is distinguished and time-honored," he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Mubarak highlighted the importance of
maintaining Sudan's stability and unity, while Zubeir briefed him
on the developments in his country, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
In a move seen as a Sudanese overture to mend fence with Egypt,
Salih arrived here this morning on a lightning visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Sudanese-Egyptian ties will be put back on track
for the good of the two peoples," the minister said, adding that
the Sudanese delegation will convey Mubarak's views to the
Sudanese leadership.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of Salih's visit, Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir told
the parliament earlier this month that his government seeks
improving battered ties with neighboring countries, especially
"sister Egypt." His initiative drew support from the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the two countries met late last month
on the fringe of the U.N. General Assembly meeting, signaling that
the two countries are working to move towards better ties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Sudanese Information Minister Tabib Ibrahim
Mohammed Khair, also called for talks with Egypt to resolve
disputes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Egypt have contested ownership of Halaib, a triangle
of land located between the two countries, since Sudan's
independence in 1956.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government also took over the Cairo University
campus in Khartoum, renaming the institution Neelein, or the two
Niles.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Egypt and Sudan have been strained since
el-Bashir took power in Sudan in 1989 and worsened in 1995 when
Cairo accused Khartoum of involvement in an assassination attempt
on Mubarak in Addis Ababa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Customs Halts Falcon Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers on Tuesday
discovered 16 falcons in the luggage of a Pakistani businessman,
who was suspected of smuggling, according to Beijing Customs
officials.
</P>
<P>
The falcons were discovered in two suitcases just before they
were loaded aboard plan bound for Kuala Lumpur. Customs officers
of Beijing have recovered 62 falcons this year.
</P>
<P>
The case, involving the businessman who worked as representative
of a Pakistani firm in Urumqi in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, will be handled by Chinese judicial departments.
</P>
<P>
The rare species, which is under state protection, has been a
target of smugglers in pursuit of high profits. Trained falcons
sell for as much as 100,000 US dollars in some countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
