<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Make Rupee Convertible by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram has said the Indian currency, the rupee, will be made
fully and freely convertible by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"India is on way to making the rupee fully and freely
convertible to any currency by the year 2000," the Press Trust of
India quoted Chidambaram as saying at an international conference
on finance and infrastructure here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rupee, which is currently convertible on the current
account, will be extended to the capital account as well, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed optimism that India would be able to wipe out
poverty from the country by the year 2020 if the present growth
rate of 7 percent sustains.
</P>
<P>
By then, the country will have raised its per capita gross
domestic product from the current 350 U.S. dollars to 1,500
dollars, providing enough resources to eliminate poverty, he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
