<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reporters Shown Around Construction Site of Three Gorges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Kim Sang-Chul could not help
marveling at the grandeur of the scene, though it was the third
time for the correspondent of the Republic of Korea to visit the
construction site of the Three Gorges water conservation project.
</P>
<P>
Speaking fluent Chinese, the Beijing Bureau correspondent of
the Munhwa Broadcasting Corp. of the Republic of Korea said that
the Three Gorges project will surely "make a great contribution to
China's future."
</P>
<P>
It will enhance flood-control along the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River, and the hydropower station will be the largest in
the world, he said, predicting that a tourism site will emerge
here and local residents will benefit from an abundance of job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Kim Sang-Chul, more than 20 reporters from a
dozen Hong Kong newspapers and from the China branches of news
organizations of countries such as Britain, France, Finland and
Ireland visited the construction site today.
</P>
<P>
The tour was sponsored by the Information Office of the State
Council just before the final damming of China's longest river on
November 8.
</P>
<P>
Li Junlin, a senior engineer with the China Yangtze River Three
Gorges Development Corp., was bombarded with reporters' questions
during their three-hour visit.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five days, the reporters had visited some
reservoir areas in Chongqing, Fuling and Wanxian to cover the
resettlement of local residents, environmental protection and the
protection of cultural relics in the area.
</P>
<P>
Kim Sang-Chul said that the TV station where he is employed
often airs programs related to the Three Gorges, for people in his
country show much interest in the gigantic flood-control and
hydro-power project in their neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Conor O'Clery, an Asia correspondent of the Irish times, said
his countrymen feel the same.
</P>
<P>
The Irish are interested in events in China, and almost all of
them have heard about the Yangtze River and the Three Gorges
project, he said.
</P>
<P>
The scale, technology and construction speed left a deep
impression on him, and the resettlement of local residents is an
intriguing topic for the press. So, the Irish Times will set aside
a whole page for him to cover the project, he said.
</P>
<P>
Isaac H. Y. Tam, a reporter with the Sing Tao Daily in Hong
Kong, said that the newspaper will publish a special edition on
the day of the damming's completion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
