<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Congress on AIDS Ends in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Fourth International
Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacific ended here today with
calls for enhanced regional cooperation and more government
budgets for fighting against the disease.
</P>
<P>
"We hereby resolve to build a sustainable network of exchange
and collaboration (in the anti-AIDS campaign)," said the Manila
Manifesto, which was adopted at the end of the five-day congress.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto committed to increasing the allocation of funds
in national and local budgets through innovation and advocacy and
developing a strategy for the sustainable provision of appropriate
treatments and social support for all people infected with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto also called for more attention to vulnerability,
risk and harm reduction relating to HIV/AIDS and for abolishing
the sexual exploitation of children, youth and women.
</P>
<P>
HIV is the human immuno-deficiency virus that causes AIDS
(acquired immuno-deficiency syndrome).
</P>
<P>
The congress, attended by nearly 3,000 delegates from 65
countries and regions, discussed the status of HIV/AIDS in the
Asia-Pacific region, socio-economic impacts related to HIV/AIDS in
the region and ways to check the spread of the lethal disease.
</P>
<P>
In parallel to the meeting, a mammoth exhibition was held to
display publications about and medicines and efforts made by all
countries against the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the U.N. Joint Program Against
AIDS, about 5 million to 7 million people are believed to be
living with HIV in the Asia-Pacific region, out of an estimated
total of 22.6 million HIV-affected persons worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth International Congress on AIDS in the Asia and the
Pacific will be held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Bu Ends 15,000 KM Centennial Olympic Tour (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese journalist Bu Fanzhou
Wednesday completed a 15,000 km bicycle journey in Sydney after
visiting each of the 21 host cities of the Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Bu, a 39-year-old journalist for the China Sports magazine,
took a 16 month journey and was met in front of the Sydney Opera
House by John Coates, president of the Australian Olympic
Committee, Phil Coles, member of the International Olympic
Committee, and Hua Junduo, Chinese Ambassador to Australia.
</P>
<P>
His mission was to experience both mentally and physically what
the Olympic spirit entails. He diarised his experience and taken
about 20,000 pictures.
</P>
<P>
The journey, or as he put it, the Centennial Olympic Tour, has
long been a dream of Bu.
</P>
<P>
He said it is the first time a journalist has retraced the
history of the modern Olympic Games by cycling to all host cities.
</P>
<P>
"It was a dream for me to take the Olympic tour," Bu told
reporters in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"And also it's a very difficult jouney, especially in Mexico
City where I was robbed of my Nikon camera by two gunmen who got
on the taxi he was traveling in broad daylight."
</P>
<P>
The taxi driver was apparently part of the robbery plot, he
said.
</P>
<P>
But most of his tour was pleasant for him. He said he could not
forget a Korean girl who offered to lead the way last winter to
Seoul, the capital of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The girl, a sports teacher, drove a car in front of him at a
speed of about 15 km an hour, and helped him, who speaks some
English, overcome language problems during part of his journey in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"I asked her why she offered to help me, a stranger, and she
replied 'you don't know the way to Seoul and does not understand
the local language. You need help. That's it'," Bu recalled.
</P>
<P>
He said he covered part of his tour by plane or ship.
</P>
<P>
With a tent in his bag, he started his journey on July 1 last
year in Athens, the home of the modern Olympics and the host city
of the 2004 Games.
</P>
<P>
Bu traveled through 17 countries on four continents, including
Greece, the United States, Japan, the Republic of Korea, Spain,
Italy, Germany, Holland, Belgium, France, Britain, Sweden,
Finland, Russia, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The graduate from Beijing University has been a sports
journalist and photographer with the China Sports magazine since
1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
