<HEADLINE> Jordan: Ties With Israel Damaged by Likud Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Frustrated by the stalled Mideast
talks and enraged by a bungled Israeli spy action in Amman, Jordan
admitted that ties with Israel have been damaged three years after
a bilateral peace treaty was signed.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio today,
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali accused Israel of
supporting state terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed a fight against terrorism while it was involved
in terrorism itself, he said, alluding to last month's failed
attempt by Israeli intelligent agents on a Hamas leader Khalid
Mashaal in Amman.
</P>
<P>
"Such Israeli actions in addition to the Likud government's
intransigence vis-a-vis the peace process have negatively affected
Jordanian-Israeli ties," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Jordan's King Hussein, Israel's closest Arab friend,
also expressed frustration over the policies of Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has frequently criticized Netanyahu for stalemate in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt are the only two Arab countries that signed
peace treaties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov's Amman
trip, Majali said Jordan felt a Russian readiness to play a more
active role in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official has not submitted a fresh initiative but
discussed ways of pushing forward the negotiating process, Majali
said in the interview conducted on the phone from Amman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
