<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Indonesian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China pays close attention to
developing a long-term and stable relationship with Indonesia and
other members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) marked by good-neighborliness and mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng made the remark here today in a meeting
with Bacharudin Jusuf Habibie, Indonesia's state minister for
research and technology.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Indonesia has worked for the development of
friendly relations between members of the ASEAN and China and
China-ASEAN ties as a whole over the past years -- something China
appreciates very much.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that China and the ASEAN members will
increase mutual understanding, trust and cooperation in the years
to come.
</P>
<P>
Li recalled his meeting with Habibie during a visit to
Indonesia in Bandung in 1990, when the two countries restored
their diplomatic relations. Since then, they have seen a steady
development in the bilateral relationship, and reached some
important agreements on both regional and international issues, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government stresses the need to advance science and
technology, Li said. He also pointed out that national
revitalization through science and education and sustained
development have been listed as two strategies for China's
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has established cooperative relations on
science and technology with more than 130 countries or regions,
and is fully prepared to expand cooperation with Indonesia in
science, technology and other areas on the basis of equality,
mutual benefit and complementary advantages.
</P>
<P>
Habibie told Li Peng that Indonesian President Soeharto
underlines the importance of relations with China, and hopes that
the two countries will bolster bilateral cooperation in the areas
of economy, culture, science and technology, and increase
personnel exchanges.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto also believes that the two countries should
approach their relationship with a view toward the 21st century,
Habibie said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
