<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea Opens Bond Market to Encourage Foreign Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 29 (Xinhua) -- In a desperate move to stabilize
the shaky financial sector, the South Korean government will open
the domestic bond market wider and earlier than scheduled, a top
economic policy-maker said today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Finance and Economy Kang
Kyong-shik said in a special statement that the government will
also encourage private enterprises to drastically expand their
offshore borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Kang also called on investors to refrain from foreign currency
speculation and "impulsively" selling off stocks.
</P>
<P>
As parts of the effort to stabilize the foreign exchange
market, Kang said the government will speed up the time for
opening the long-term corporate bond market to early next year
instead of the originally-scheduled 1999 or soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Investment limits on large companies' non-guaranteed
convertible bonds (CBs) will be raised from the current 30 percent
for all foreign investors to 50 percent and from 6 percent for
individual investors to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
For non-guaranteed CBs and medium- and long-term bonds issued by
small businesses, the existing foreign investment limits will be
lifted.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the current instability in the foreign exchange
market has been triggered by indiscriminate buying of U.S. dollars
by domestic financial institutions, Kang said the government will
impose a purchase limit to deter speculation.
</P>
<P>
Unlike widespread expectations, however, the government has
decided not to mobilize any special central bank loans to
stabilize the local bourse. Neither was an additional increase in
the foreign equity ownership limit included in the special
measures, said financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Kang encouraged pension funds and institutional
players to invest in the sagging bourse.
</P>
<P>
He said despite the latest jitters in stock and money markets,
the nation's macro-economic fundamentals are constantly improving.
</P>
<P>
The lack of a dignified market booster, however, may dash cold
water on the local bourse, which showed a minor gain on the day
due to a technical rebound and hopes of a more drastic boosting
package, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
