<HEADLINE> No Massive Redemption by Funds in Equity Market, Managers Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- There was no massive
redemption by mutual funds in the past week on the severely
battered Hong Kong stock market as well as other major bourses
across the world, fund managers said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Fund is a long-term savings vehicle," said Chris Russell from
the Hong Kong Investment Funds Association, who chaired an
organizing committee for the just-concluded International
Investment Funds Conference.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for an Asian city outside Tokyo to host
the private event, which attracted more than 50 senior managers
representing 27 investment funds associations from all the world.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a very befitting venue for the 1997 conference
since people engaged in the industry can eye for themselves "the
confidence going forward in Hong Kong from July 1", said Russell.
</P>
<P>
Topics touched upon during the two-day discussion included
strengths of mutual funds, emerging pension markets, mutual fund
governance structure and emerging market clearance and settlement
system.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the United States, Europe and Japan
outlined at today's press conference the latest developments in
the mutual fund and unit trust industry in their respective
markets.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the impact of the recently savaged stock markets on
their funds, they claimed they did not see large volume
redemption.
</P>
<P>
Takashi Hinata, vice chairman of the Investment Trusts
Association of Japan, said equity investment only constituted a
small 11 percent of their investment portfolios. "We don't see so
far much redemption."
</P>
<P>
"I'm not too much concerned about Tokyo market," which fell
significantly in the past several days because "the foreign
exchange rate is stable and economic fundamentals are sound," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also expected the current turbulence in Hong Kong market to
get settled in near future.
</P>
<P>
Julian Tregoning, president of the European Federation of
Investment Funds and Companies, spoke highly of what the Hong Kong
government has done in stabilizing the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said that compared with a few years ago, Hong Kong's
financial mechanism has turned more mature with volumes traded at
the stock exchange multiplying.
</P>
<P>
He played down the fluctuations on the local market, saying
stocks up and stocks down are a very natural phenomenon that every
investor should understand.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong shares are very cheap at the current level, he said.
"I'm more willing to buy now than three months ago." 
</P>
</TEXT>
