<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Urban Water-Diversion Project Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China's largest urban
water-diversion project was completed in Dalian in northeast
China's Liaoning Province on Tuesday. It took three years to
build, one year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to bring in water from the Biliu River,
which is over 150 km away from this coastal open city, which has a
population of 2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
According to officials in charge of the project, the project,
with a daily water-supply of 1.2 million tons, cost three billion
yuan, 500 million yuan less than originally planned. The Asian
Development Bank (ADB) offered 1.4 billion yuan in loans for the
work.
</P>
<P>
International practices have been adopted in the project,
including public bidding and quality supervision, the officials
say.
</P>
<P>
The project was initiated in 1994, when the city government
took steps to resolve the severe water-shortage.
</P>
<P>
Dalian is one of the largest industrial cities in the country
and is also home to over 6,000 Sino-foreign joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Bo Xilai told Xinhua that the city government is
considering launching more water-introduction projects in future,
so as to ensure the city's sustained development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
