<HEADLINE> HK to Maintain Low, Simple Tax Regime: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is firmly committed
to a low, simple and predictable tax regime, Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang said here today.
</P>
<P>
Nothing substantial has changed with respect to taxation since
Hong Kong entered into the new era on July 1, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure you that we are going to keep our tax law very,
very much simpler than the 9,451 pages of the U.S. tax code, to
which the latest budget agreement in the U.S. added another 285
new sections and 824 amendments," Tsang told the annual luncheon
of the Board of Review (Inland Revenue).
</P>
<P>
He estimated that total government revenue receipts in the
1997-1998 year will reach 235 billion HK dollars (30.1 billion
U.S. dollars) and that the fiscal reserves will exceed 400 billion
HK dollars (51.3 billion U.S. dollars) by the end of this
financial year.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 50th anniversary of the Board of Review,
which was constituted in 1947 upon enactment of the Inland Revenue
Ordinance, to deal with appeal cases raised by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Tsang told the board: "We are currently conducting a
comprehensive review on profits tax to examine whether we can make
our taxation system and business environment more competitive. The
public consultation period ended in early September."
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the relatively simple taxation system,
there may well be areas which are not sufficiently clear and which
may give rise to disputes over tax assessment.
</P>
<P>
"One area which we must certainly address is to enhance
certainty in the operation of the taxation system. This should
help to clear gray areas in tax assessment and reduce the
opportunity for disputes, and thus the need for appeal," he said.
</P>
<P>
The number of appeal cases received has increased substantially
in the past several years.
</P>
<P>
The use of Chinese language has been introduced in Board
proceedings. Up to now, more than 20 cases were heard in Chinese
during this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
