<HEADLINE> Nigeria Welcomes Commonwealth Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria yesterday welcomed the
Commonwealth decision to hold any further actions against it
until next year, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is a good thing that they support our transition
program," Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi told newsmen at the
Lagos airport last night.
</P>
<P>
He said the Nigerian government will study the communique of
the Commonwealth summit of heads of government that ended Monday
in Edinburgh, Scotland, and will work upon it.
</P>
<P>
He also defended the country's human rights record and said
that Nigeria could not be isolated internationally.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth summit refused suggestions by some
pro-democracy groups that Nigeria be expelled from the 54-nation
organization and be imposed of fresh sanctions.
</P>
<P>
It, however, warned that Nigeria will suffer new sanctions
including oil embargo, if there is no progress in the transition
program by October next year.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership in November
1995 after its government executed author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
other minority activists on charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian military government led by General Sani Abacha
has announced a transition program which promises to return power
to elected civilian government by October next year.
</P>
<P>
As part of the transition program, the government has approved
the registration of five political parties and has held a local
election on party basis in March, which is generally regarded as
free and fair.
</P>
<P>
Some pro-democracy groups, however, have criticized the
government of being insincere in implementing the transition
program. They also hold that the government has not done enough
in improving its human rights records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
