<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Foreign Debt Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's foreign debt profile
went down by 1.048 billion U.S. Dollars in the six months of this
year, Finance Minister Anthony Ani announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign debt overhang was reduced from 28.06 billion
dollars on December 31, 1996 to 27.012 billion dollars at the end
of June this year, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ani denied the figure of around 34 billion dollars
provided by the World Bank and International Monetary Fund,
saying that the government had done a thorough job of
ascertaining the accuracy of the figures.
</P>
<P>
Th minister noted that the differentials between the figures
arose because the nation's debt for budget purposes were
converted to U.S. dollars while in actual fact the loans that
constitute the debt stock were obtained in various currencies.
</P>
<P>
He also attributed the differentials to the fact that some of
the debts to some creditors of the Paris Club were still included
in the debt stock despite the fact that the debts had been paid
off.
</P>
<P>
"Our debt stock is to some extent determined by the movement
of currencies in the capital market," Ani told a seminar on the
country's debt problem, organized by the Central Bank of Nigeria
in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said that the appreciation of the dollar
against the Japanese yen by 29 percent in which some of the loans
were denominated had led to a reduction of the debt stock.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been seeking to expand export and reduce foreign
debt in its bid to stabilize the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the finance minister announced an embargo on new
foreign loans in July this year, saying that new loans would not
be allowed until the bulk of its current debt was paid.
</P>
<P>
The policy, along with others implemented so far would
continue until the debt stock service ratio attains a sustainable
level, Ani reiterated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Senior Official on Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chemical Weapons
Convention (CWC) would serve as an effective disarmament
instrument only when all countries possessing such weapons
strictly adhere to its provisions, Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad said here today.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial for the success of the CWC that all possessors
of chemical weapons must become parties to the convention and
adhere to its provisions, including the complete and speedy
destruction of chemical weapons stockpiles," Shamshad said at a
news briefing here a day after Pakistan's Instrument of
Ratification to the CWC was deposited with the United Nations
Secretary General Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Only then would the convention serve as an effective
disarmament instrument," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, an original signatory to the CWC in January 1993,
delayed its ratification of the convention because of the
completion of the process in this regard, Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad described the CWC as "an international legal
framework" for the realization of complete prohibition and
thorough destruction of all chemical weapons and their production
facilities.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Pakistan's support for the convention but
emphasized that all its provisions "must be implemented in an
objective and faithful manner."
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary also pointed out that Pakistan "will at
all times retain its sovereign right to take all necessary
measures to protect its national security interests" while
adopting necessary measures and establishing necessary procedures
to implement its obligations under the convention.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan will exercise its rights to indicate its
non-acceptance of inspectors and inspection assistants as it deems
appropriate," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
