<HEADLINE> Sudanese Vice President Visits Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese First Vice President
el-Zubeir Mohammad Salih arrived here today on a visit designed to
improve Cairo-Khartoum ties.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Agriculture
Youssef Amin Youssef Wali welcomed Salih at the airport, the
Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not mention who will attend talks with Salih
on behalf of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of Salih's visit, Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir told
the parliament that his government seeks improving relations with
Arab countries, particularly Egypt. His initiative drew support
from the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Noticeably, Sudanese newspapers turn out to be clear from
routine criticism against Egypt, flashing "sisterly Egypt"
instead, according to MENA.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the two countries met late last month
on the fringe of the U.N. General Assembly meeting, signaling that
the two countries are working to move towards better ties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Sudanese Information Minister Tabib Ibrahim
Mohammed Khair, called for talks with Egypt to resolve disputes
between the the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Egypt have contested ownership of Halaib, a triangle
of land located between the two countries, since Sudan's
independence in 1956.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government also took over the Cairo University
campus in Khartoum, renaming the institution Neelein, or the two
Niles.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Egypt and Sudan have been strained since
el-Bashir took power in Sudan in 1989 and worsened in 1995 when
Cairo accused Khartoum of involvement in an assassination attempt
on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
