<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Cast Off Losses, Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
did a backflip today as it recovered from Tuesday's 18 billion
U.S. dollar loss and bargain hunters flooded the local bourse.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed up 143.8 points at 2443.0, just
58.4 points off its intra-day high of 2501.4, after the Australian
Stock Exchange (ASX) shut down early, snowed under by a record
number of trades.
</P>
<P>
The ASX issued a statement apologizing for the 20 minute early
close, sparked by the inability of its trading system to cope with
more than 60,000 trades in one day.
</P>
<P>
The rise came on the back of massive trade on Wall Street
overnight which saw the Dow Jones Industrial Average record its
biggest ever one day gain.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richmond, Peake Lands Kirwan broker, said the frantic
day's trade was unparalleled in Australia's history.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ASX said a record 62,497 trades were
recorded, 2,497 more than the system's 60,000 capacity. This
compared to the previous record of 50,979.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank finished the day 87.5 cents up at 9.96 Australian
dollars after being a notable tumbler Tuesday, while other banking
stocks also closed higher.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was up 79 cents up at 19.64 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth bank was 1.15 Australian dollars higher at
16.05 Australian dollars and Westpac gained 25 cents to end at
8.00 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed up 55.9 points at 1139.9 while
the all industrials finished up 253.4 points at 4089.2.
</P>
<P>
Major resource stocks that were sold well down Tuesday regained
their ground today with mining giant WMC jumping 30 cents to 5.20
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto closed up 74.7 cents at 16.80 Australian
dollars while market bellwether BHP added 17 cents to 13.97
Australian dollars but well below the day's highs.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks soared this morning, with the index up more than 10
percent at noon, before settling 78.8 points or 7.96 percent
stronger at 1068.2.
</P>
<P>
Spot gold bullion trading was 315.15 U.S. dollars, 3.65 U.S.
dollars stronger.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 515.20 million shares at a value of 1.3
billion Australian dollars (917 million U.S. dollars), with rises
greatly outnumbering falls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
