<HEADLINE> Israel Partially Reopens Controversial Street in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel today partially
reopened a controversial street in the flashpoint West Bank city
Hebron according to the Hebron agreement signed in last January.
</P>
<P>
In the heavy presence of Israeli soldiers deployed to prevent
possible clashes between Jewish settlers and Palestinian
residents, the Shuhada Street, or Martyrs' Street, was partially
opened early this morning to both Israeli and Palestinian traffic.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military governor of Hebron Baruch Najar said that
Israel opened the 400-meter section as a test, adding the rest of
the street would be opened if the first stage goes well without
trouble, local radios reported.
</P>
<P>
Only authorized vehicles would be allowed to travel through it
under strict scrutiny of the Israeli soldiers. Jewish settlers
feared the opening of the street would enable Palestinian
militants to launch terror attacks against settlers living by the
roadside, such as car bombings or drive-by shootings.
</P>
<P>
Shuhada Street was closed three years ago after a Jewish
settler shot dead 29 Palestinian prayers in the Tomb of
Patriarchs, or Ibrahim Mosque called by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron agreement that led to Israeli troop withdrawal
from 80 percent of the city in January, the street has been
beautified with 2.5 million dollars donated by the United
States. Following the redeployment, Israeli soldiers remained to
guard the rest 20 percent area where about 450 Jewish settlers are
still living.
</P>
<P>
Despite Israel's move today, the Palestinians still demanded
for full opening of the street. Palestinian Mayor Mustafa Natche
accused Israel of failing to open the street totally for
Palestinians while imposing no limits on the Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
For months, settlers in the city have been compaigning to
prevent the reopening of Shuhada Street. Spokesman for the Hebron
settlers Noam Arnon said the opening of the street would endanger
the security of the Jewish community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
