<HEADLINE> Australian Airline to Add Australia-China Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Qantas Airways Ltd., the
largest airline in Australia, will increase its weekly flights
between China and Australia from four to six starting April 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the same time it will reduce the number of direct flights
between Japan and the north Queensland tourist center of Cairns.
</P>
<P>
Two new weekly non-stop China-Brisbane flights would be
introduced, bringing to six the airline's weekly frequency between
China and Australia, said Geoff Dixon, Qantas' executive general
manager commercial said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
One of the flights will link the Chinese capital Beijing and
Brisbane, the capital of the Queensland state in northeast
Australia, while the other will operate between China's eastern
coastal city Shanghai and Brisbane, Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
Queensland, Australia's major tourist destination, has been the
leading foreign exchange earner in Australia's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Qantas also rescheduled its services between Japan and Cairns,
a coastal city in northeast Australia, to cater for existing
demand and projected growth.
</P>
<P>
Dixon said from April next year, two of Qantas' five weekly
Fukuoka-Cairns-Sydney flights would switch to non-stop services
between Fukuoka and Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Also from April, the weekly Osaka-Cairns and Tokyo-Brisbane
services would be discontinued.
</P>
<P>
The twice-weekly Sapporo-Cairns service would be suspended
between April and October next year.
</P>
<P>
Dixon said Qantas would schedule an extra peak-season
Auckland-Cairns flight to bring to three the weekly services
linking Los Angeles in the United States with Cairns via Auckland
in New Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
