<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislators Consider Proposed Law on Fire Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua)--The proposed law on fire control
was submitted here today to the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, China's top legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the proposal, Minister of Public Security Tao Siju
said that China has confronted severe challenges in fire control
in the last decade, a time of rapid economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
More tall and multi-functional buildings have been erected
without adequate preparation for fire prevention and control.
</P>
<P>
"A generally weak awareness of fire prevention and outdated
firefighting facilities, including an inadequate number of fire
stations, lack of water supply and express lanes for fire-fighting
equipment have contributed to heavy losses in human lives and
property," Tao said.
</P>
<P>
The 1984 State Council regulation on fire control cannot cope
with the changing situation, he said, and imposes a very light
punishment on those responsible for fire accidents. The current
penalty is 100 yuan and less than 10 days' detention for severe
cases.
</P>
<P>
The proposed fire control law has 47 articles in six chapters
covering fire prevention, organization, fire-fighting, first aid
and legal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The proposed law would beef up firefighting infrastructures and
management. Inspections would be required for schools, hospitals,
social welfare institutions and places such as cinemas, ballrooms,
shopping malls, big hotels and restaurants before they would be
allowed to open to the public.
</P>
<P>
Organizers for large gatherings such as mass rallies, fireworks
demonstrations and lantern festivals would be required to submit
their plans for firefighting and crowd control.
</P>
<P>
To minimize casualties, the proposed law requires workers at
public places to help people safely exit in case of fire. Those
who fail to perform their legal obligation and flee for their own
safety would face severe penalties under the law.
</P>
<P>
The proposed law also increases the penalty for arsonists. For
example, those responsible for causing a fire that leads to heavy
losses would face criminal charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
