<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Sends Letter to UN Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has recently sent a letter to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, accusing the European Union (EU) of interfering in the
Cyprus problem, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Denktash's letter was in response to Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides' recent speech at the U.N. General Assembly, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said in his letter that the EU's "untimely
interference" in the Cyprus problem had had the most profound
effect on the U.N.-sponsored direct talks between the two Cypriot
communities' leaders.
</P>
<P>
The current impasse in the inter-communal talks was not due to
any precondition brought to the table by the Turkish Cypriot side,
Denktash claimed.
</P>
<P>
The last round of direct talks between Denktash and Clerides in
Glion in Switzerland in August ended in deadlock as the Turkish
Cypriot side insisted Cyprus-EU negotiations be postponed pending
a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The EU reaffirmed its decision in July this year that the
accession talks with Cyprus will begin in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish Cypriot side cannot be expected to watch
helplessly while the EU takes concrete steps to convert Cyprus
into a Greek state," Denktash said in the letter to Annan.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader pointed out that there were four
conditions the Turkish Cypriot side would not
relinquish: sovereignty, security and guarantees; political
equality; the maintenance of the balance between Turkey and Greece
established by the 1960 agreements; and a bi-zonal system
reinforced by the exchange of properties.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the Turkish Cypriots' equal status is not
recognized, the Greek Cypriots will continue to undermine every
initiative," Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Denktash would soon travel to New York to
have meetings with Annan and U.S. Presidential Emissary Richard
Holbrooke on Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The East Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island following a short-lived pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
