<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Tombs of Slaves Buried Alive Found in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered two ancient tombs in the eastern suburbs of Xi'an City,
capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province. Three slaves had
been buried alive in the tomb with their deceased masters,
archaeologists said.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said the tombs were built between 557 A.D. and
618 A.D. in the Northern Zhou Dynasty and the Sui Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The two tombs with the rare find are among four recently
discovered ancient sites in the city's suburban area.
</P>
<P>
According to a gravestone inside the largest tomb, a
61-year-old official of the Northern Zhou Dynasty and his wife
were buried in the coffin chamber. The official died in 573 A.D. A
nine-year-old slave was buried alive in the eastern niche of the
coffin chamber. Two other slaves were buried alive in the eastern
and western niches of another tomb along with other members of the
master's family.
</P>
<P>
Sacrificial objects found in the tomb include jade rings, clay
figures of worriers, pottery and coins.
</P>
<P>
The practice of burying the slaves with their deceased masters
was prevalent in China between 2,000 and 3,000 years ago.
However, tombs with slaves buried alive were seldom discovered.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the discovery of the two ancient tombs are of
great importance to the research of the Northern Zhou Dynasty and
Sui Dynasty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
