<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recognition Urged for Sign Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 29 (Xinhua)--Ethiopian government has
been urged to approve sign language as any other language and
allow the disabled to take part in every sort of social
activities fit for them.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Mengesha Hale-Melekot, general manager of
the rehabilitation department of the Ministry of Labor and Social
Affairs at a meeting here Tuesday to mark the 5th international
week of the deaf in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Mengesha said although the rights of the deaf have been fully
ensured over the past five years more than ever, sign language
has not yet won legal recognition.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government has given due attention to the
desires and abilities of the deaf besides creating enabling
situation whereby they could contribute a lot to the social and
economic development of the nation.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, some fields of work are still closed to the
deaf.
</P>
<P>
He also called on journalists to give coverage to the creative
works of the deaf which include, among others,literature, drama,
paintings and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
This year's International Week of the Deaf is observed in
Ethiopia from October 28 to November 1 under the theme "human
rights and dignity for the deaf through legal protection."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
