<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Raises Tariff on Imported Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
raised tariff on imported wheat from 25 percent to 50 percent in
order to protect local farmers from unfair competition, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Minister Darius Mbela told Kenyan Parliament
Tuesday that the new tariff took effect on Monday, adding that
the measures were expected to adequately protect local farmers as
international wheat prices had been falling.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the new duty would push the cost of
buying and shipping a bag of wheat (90 kilograms) from 1.100
Kenyan Shillings (about 18 U.S. Dollars) to 1.500 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
He made the ministerial statement at the Parliament on the
request of parliament members to explain the situation of the
wheat in the East African country following disagreements on
prices between wheat farmers and millers.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Uasin Gishu District, west Kenya, are insisting on
1.800 Shillings per 90-kg bag of wheat while the millers are
offering a price of 1.350 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Since the wheat sector was liberalized in 1993, the Kenyan
government has ceased setting prices for wheat and wheat
products.
</P>
<P>
Cyril Nabutola, General Manager of the Unga Limited operating
in west Kenya, was quoted as saying that his company's position
on wheat prices was determined by economic factor.
</P>
<P>
The annual wheat production in Kenya stands at around 3.5
million bags compared to a demand of 7 million bags for local
consumption. Kenya has to import more than 3 million bags of
wheat annually to meet the domestic demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Securities Sector in Guangdong Growing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The securities industry in
southern China's Guangdong Province is among the most developed in
the country, official figures indicate.
</P>
<P>
A total of 110 enterprises in Guangdong have issued shares
through the two stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen, raising
funds worth more than 30 billion yuan and 14 billion Hong Kong
dollars in the aggregate, Zhang Gaoli, executive vice governor of
Guangdong Province, said today.
</P>
<P>
China had a total of 708 listed companies by the end of August,
which had a capital stock of 159.7 billion yuan and a stock market
capitalization of 1,640 billion yuan, about 24 percent of the
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The membership of the Shenzhen Stock Exchange, which is located
in Shenzhen, Guangdong Province, reached 428 by the end of last
month, while the number of trading accounts opened by investors
totaled 15.4 million, said Zhang, who is also chairman of the
provincial securities regulatory commission.
</P>
<P>
The number of companies listed on the Shenzhen exchange reached
350 by the end of last month and securities turnover at the
exchange totaled 1.38 trillion yuan in the first nine months of
this year, Zhang said, adding that Guangdong also has 17
investment funds, about 20 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
There are 4.25 million securities investors in Guangdong,
compared with more than 22 million nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is a showcase of the reforms of China's market
economy and is among the economically most-developed provinces in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
