<HEADLINE> Former Californian Governor to Run for Oakland Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Jerry Brown, former
two-term Democratic governor, announced today he is planning to
run for mayor of Oakland, a port city in northern California.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the headquarters of We the People, the 59-year-old
Brown said he is starting a grass-roots campaign and promised to
work as a catalyst for reform if elected.
</P>
<P>
Serving as governor of California from 1975 to 1983 and failing
three times in running for presidency, namely in 1976, 1980 and
1992, Brown now spreads his views as host of a radio talk show and
has long been rumored to be interested in succeeding Elihu Harris,
current second-term mayor of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
Oakland is considered one of the most ethnically complicated
cities in California, a city with 44 percent blacks, 32 percent
white and 15 percent Asian-Americans of its total population.
</P>
</TEXT>
