<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Advised Not to Take 500-won Coins to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korean tourists are advised
by the government not to carry 500-won South Korean coins to Japan
because Japanese authorities are cracking down on the illegal use
of 500-won coins as 500-yen coins (about 4,000 won).
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to punish those and confiscate their
passports who are caught in Japan carrying a large number of South
Korean coins, which can be used in vending machines in Japan as
500-yen coins with slight modifications, according to the Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"We have advised people not to carry the coins when they go
to Japan as they may be subjected to unexpected disadvantages
there," a ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The move stemmed from the South Korean government's efforts to
prevent damage of its external image that may be caused by the
increasing use of 500-won South Korean coins in Japan recently.
</P>
<P>
Japanese customs authorities have recently checked 12 people
including four South Koreans who carried a total of 24,823 coins,
and referred most of them for prosecution for violating customs
laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
