<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lianyungang Upgrades Transportation Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Lianyungang, a Chinese port
on the Yellow Sea, has been updating its facilities to enhance its
reputation as a hub for both domestic and international
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Located in Jiangsu Province, the port with 22  10,000-ton
berths is now capable of handling 20 million tons of cargo
annually. Its shipping routes are connected to hundreds of ports
in more than 150 countries.
</P>
<P>
The port also has special docks for containers and dangerous
cargo. It handled 12,118 international containers through China's
Europe-Asia Continental Bridge in 1996. Some 25,000 containers passed
through the port in the first nine months of this year, twice the
figure for the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to port improvements, 1.6 billion yuan has been
spent on highway construction in the last five years, augmenting
the railway service.
</P>
<P>
Highways and bridges are under construction to link
main north-south and east-west roads.
</P>
<P>
Lianyungang also has direct rail links to Rotterdam in the
Netherlands, running through 40 countries and regions and
connecting the Pacific Ocean with the Atlantic Ocean.  
</P>
</TEXT>
