<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artists to Paint Yangtze River Scenes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese artists are
preparing to paint a 100-meter long picture of the Yangtze River,
China's longest river.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze, which stretches some 6,300 km., is one of the
world's longest rivers.
</P>
<P>
Wu Song and Song Gang, the two young artists involved, are
currently in the Three Gorges area sketching landscapes and
features along the banks of the Yangtze River prior to its damming.
</P>
<P>
Song, a Ph.D. who studied painting in Rome, and Wu, an
associate professor at the Sichuan Academy of Fine Arts, are known
for their use of bright colors. The artists have prepared for the
project for over two years.
</P>
<P>
The painting will depict scenes from Snow Mount. Gladaindong,
the source of the Yangtze in northwest China's Qinghai Province,
to Wusongkou in Shanghai where the river empties into the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The massive painting will depict prosperity along banks of
China's longest river prior to the turn of the century, as well as
natural scenery, historic sites and cultural relices.
</P>
<P>
Another huge painting, the 150-meter long traditional Chinese
painting entitled "A New Look at the 10,000-Li Yangtze River," was
published in "Fine Arts" in 1987.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
