<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bama Centenarians Tell Secrets of Longevity (1) by Wu Xiaojun and Lu Hankui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- It's all in the diet, say some
of China's longest-living residents. A bowl of maize-flour
porridge, a plate of bean curd, a cup of corn wine and a glass of
mountain tea can do wonders for life expectancy, they say.
</P>
<P>
At least that's the experience recounted by 79 centenarians in
Bama Autonomous County of Yao Nationality in southwestern China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. Bama has a population of its
260,000.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has more than 8,000 centenarians,
most of whom live in the remote mountainous areas of northwestern,
southern and southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese capital of Beijing, only 56 centenarians were
registered out of some 11 million citizens in 1990, according to
statistics of China's fourth national census in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jinchao, head of the Bama Longevity Research Institute,
said that the diet of Bama centenarians is in accordance with
scientific research on longevity in China and some Western
countries. The mild subtropical climate in mountainous soil rich
in manganese and selenium also play a part in fostering longevity
as well as the clear river water and negative-ion enriched air.
</P>
<P>
Of the 79 Bama centenarians, Chen said 18 are males while 61
are females. The oldest is 112.
</P>
<P>
Chen's research institute analyzed the diet of Bama
centenarians who eat maize-flour porridge, rice and beans, or mung
beans as their staple food along with other beans such as soy,
jack and kidney and peas as the main dishes.
</P>
<P>
Experts say maize produced in Bama contains much more Vitamin
B-1, E and beta carotene than other areas because of the soil
conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bama Centenarians Tell Secrets of Longevity (2) by Wu Xiaojun and Lu Hankui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Besides bean curd, centenarians often eat wild vegetables as
their main dish. They consume meat, mutton or beef only two or
three times a month, however, many of them favor fatty meat.
</P>
<P>
Bama centenarians use soy bean or herbal oils which contains
linoleic acids which reduce cholesterol, metabolize fat and
encourage the regeneration of liver cells.
</P>
<P>
All of the Bama centenarians have contracted with measles; 60
of them have never visited a doctor.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the remote mountain areas have a sparse population
where infectious diseases rarely spread.
</P>
<P>
The Bama centenarians also drink wild mountain tea that is rich
in amino acids, vitamins and other micro-elements good for health
and longevity. The incidence of coronary heart disease among
centenarians in Bama is only 4.3 percent, while that of Guangzhou,
capital of the neighboring Guangdong Province in the plains area,
ranges between 29 to 38.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts say a human's need for trace elements are absorbed
through their food because crops absorb these elements from the
soil. They play an important role in people's normal growth,
resistance to diseases and longevity.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also found that many Bama centenarians daily
consume wine made from maize or a "medicinal liquor" made from
gecko lizards, poisonous and non-poisonous snakes, and traditional
Chinese medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bama Centenarians Tell Secrets of Longevity (3) by Wu Xiaojun and Lu Hankui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The medicinal liquor reportedly improves blood circulation and
relieves colds.
</P>
<P>
All the centenarians are active -- farming, household chores or
sports such as archery and hunting. Many of them have hobbies such
as chess, calligraphy and singing.
</P>
<P>
Wei Puming, 102, still hunts and Huang Jiaxiang, 103, weaves
bamboo. Lu Dihua, Lu Dimei and Lu Dixiao, three sisters ranging
from 100 to 110, still care for themselves and do household chores.
</P>
<P>
Researchers found that most of the Bama centenarians are very
active and social, and are kind to other family members and
neighbors. They are neither materialistic nor ambitious, and seem
to live for their three meals a day and their household affairs.
</P>
<P>
Most of the centenarians live in mountainous areas covered with
more than 2,000 kinds of plants. Since these areas receive fewer
hours of sunshine than the plains, crops ripen a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
Most of the centenarians live along the banks of the
145-kilometer Panyang River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Herdsmen's Children Go to College in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, October 29 (Xinhua) -- In a small village in eastern
Inner Mongolia, 164 of the 1,209 villagers are studying in
universities, colleges or secondary technical schools.
</P>
<P>
And, Golibu, a herdsman in the village Shabage on the Bairin
Grassland, is the only one who does not have a college education
in his six-member family.
</P>
<P>
Golibu gave up education after finishing junior middle school
studies. He now oversees 75 hectares of grassland and forest, and
cares for 120 cows and 160 sheep and makes at least 40,000 yuan
(5,000 US dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Many families in Shabage are similar to Golibu's, according to
Uligi, secretary of the village Party committee.
</P>
<P>
Uligi explains that, since the beginning of the 1990s,
per-capita annual income in the village has exceeded 2,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"When people make more money, the first thing they think of is
sending their children to school. The families compete with each
other to see who has more children in college, and whose children
do well in school," Uligi says. More than 80 percent of the
families have at least one child with a higher education
experience.
</P>
<P>
And, since 1991, the village has spent more than 300,000 yuan
on schools and better teachers, and 100 percent of the school-age
children are in school. When those 164 students have graduated, a
quarter of them will probably come back and work in their
hometown.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
