New Nigerian
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi said on Tuesday the survival of
Nigeria depended on the total sincerity of its citizens even as
he maintained that the country was not in any form of isolation
following the continued suspension of its membership of the
Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
-- Nigeria's first global satellite television station is set
to hit the air wave on November 3 this year as arrangements have
been concluded for the commissioning of the Africa International
Television by the head of state General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian
</P>
<P>
-- General Sani Abacha said on Tuesday that Nigeria would not
be intimidated by "orchestrated international hostility" and
would maintain an ability to defend fundemental Nigerian
interests.
</P>
<P>
-- Of the 13.7 billion U.S. dollars external loans procured by
Nigeria to a variety of projects, 836.2 million dollars has been
lost to ghost projects in various parts of the country, according
to Finance Minister Anthony Ani.
</P>
<P>
This Day
</P>
<P>
-- The Nigerian government has condemned in very strong terms
the reported moves by the European Parliament to provide some 3.6
million dollars as special aid to pro-democracy and human rights
campaigners in the country to fight the Abacha government next
year, saying the offer was nothing but an attempt to destabilize
the country.
</P>
<P>
-- Nigeria's external debt profile went down by 1.048 billion
dollars in the first six months of this year, Finance Minister
Anthony Ani said on Tuesday.  
