<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Opposition to Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi has reiterated Iran's opposition to
the forthcoming Middle East and North African (MENA) economic
conference.
</P>
<P>
Local radios quoted Mohammadi as saying Thursday such a
conference would not be in the benefit of Islamic solidarity,
adding that Tehran had earlier informed Qatar of Iran's stance
towards the conference, to be held in Qatari capital Doha from
November 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi stressed that Israel and the United States had
always been trying to create a cleft among the Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab countries, such as Lebanon, Syria, the United Arab
Emirates and Saudi Arabia have threatened to boycott the
Israeli-present conference, in protest against Israeli
government's hardline policy towards the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai's recent remarks
terming Iran as a threat to the security of the Middle East,
Mohammadi said that the objective behind "Israeli regime's
dissemination of misinformation and disinformation is to deviate
public attention from the realities of the region."
</P>
<P>
Israel and the United States have allegedly believed that Iran
has the capacity to produce ballistic missiles threatening Israel
and the U.S. interests in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Mordechai said, Israel reserves the right of
attacking targets such as the Iranian long-range missile bases,
threatening that those who would be involved in targeting Israeli
sensitive systems should expect to pay a high price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
