<HEADLINE> Air Transport Capacity to Increase in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 29 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
will import four Airbus Industrie planes to increase its air
transport capacity over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The province already has one A320 airliner, the local aviation
department says. Over the past five years, it has greatly improved
its air transport by increasing the number of airports to seven
and opening more than 100 air routes.
</P>
<P>
An aviation network, with the provincial capital of Hangzhou as
the center, connecting the cities of Ningbo, Wenzhou, Huangyan,
Yiwu, Quzhou, and Zhoushan, has been established.
</P>
<P>
It has handled more than 18 million passengers and roughly
300,000 tons of goods over the past five years, giving an annual
growth rate of 25 percent on average, one of the highest of
China's air carriers.
</P>
<P>
The air transport boom has contributed a lot to the local
economy, especially foreign trade and tourism, and Zhejiang's
annual economic growth rate was more than ten percent over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
It plans to build the Xiaoshan International Airport in
Hangzhou, at a cost of over three billion yuan, to further improve
air transportation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
