<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Foreign Minister Visits Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab
Chaiyasarn arrived here today on a two-day official visit to
Myanmar in a bid to strengthen bilateral relations between the two
countries and coordination on ASEAN issues.
</P>
<P>
It is Prachuab's second visit to Myanmar in this year. The
first one was in May when he accompanied Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh on his official trip to the country.
</P>
<P>
Prachuab is expected to have talks with his Myanmar counterpart
U Ohn Gyaw on bilateral cooperation as well as regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, one of Myanmar's five major trading partners,
formally reached a border trade agreement with myanmar in March
1996 to carry out trade activities at three border points. The
volume of trade between the two countries amounted to 450 million
U.S. dollars in the year, according to Thai official sources.
</P>
<P>
A Myanmar-Thai friendship bridge on the Moei (Thaungyin) River
linking border towns of Myawaddy of Myanmar and Maesot of Thailand
was also opened later in August, facilitating trade, transport and
communications between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In the same month, meetings of Myanmar-Thai Joint Border
Committee, chaired by deputy foreign ministers, and Regional
Border committee, chaired by regional commanders, were held in
Thailand's Bangkok and Chiang Rai respectively.
</P>
<P>
To improve transport links between the two countries, Myanmar
and Thailand have planed to develop two deep-sea ports -- one in
Thailand's Bagn Saphan on the Gulf of Thailand and the other in
Myanmar's Bokpyin area beside the Andaman Sea.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, one of the leading foreign investors in Myanmar,
ranked third after the United Kingdom and Singapore with 1.15
billion U.S. dollars in 42 permitted projects out of
6.44-billion-dollars' total foreign investment at the end of
September this year, covering sectors of oil and gas, hotels and
tourism, livestock breeding and fishery, industry estate and
transport.  
</P>
</TEXT>
