<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Court Suspends Operation of Anti-Defection Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Pakistan
today suspended the operation of the Anti-Defection Law. Therefore
no adverse action will be taken against members of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah, head of the three member bench,
pronounced a short order on a petition regarding the
Anti-Defection Law.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court took the decision at the crucial moment when
the government and the Judiciary are trying to resolve the
two-month-old tussle over the elevation of judges.
</P>
<P>
The decision also came hours before the National Assembly
session scheduled for this evening in which the government is
likely to pass a bill restricting the sanctioned strength of the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
"In the circumstances it is proper to grant interim relief. No
adverse action is allowed to be taken against the members of the
Parliament in pursuance of newly added article 63(a) in the
Constitution, till the final disposal of the petition," said the
Chief Justice in the order.
</P>
<P>
If a member of the Parliament will be dissident, there will be
no action against him, he added.
</P>
<P>
The order further said, "Initially, we were of the view that
proceedings should be concluded and final order may be passed as
early as possible. But, due to the gravity of the situation, and
the act of the parliament under consideration, it is not possible
to conclude the proceedings."
</P>
<P>
Members of the parliament feel that in the presence of such
provision, if they express freely their candid opinions, they may
lose their seats. So, it is fit and proper to grant interim
relief, the order further said.
</P>
<P>
Before announcing the judgment, the three member bench heard
the arguments of Attorney General Chaudhry Muhammad Farooq, who
was of the opinion that the Anti-Defection Law was introduced to
strengthen democracy and check horse-trading.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Defection Law, or the 14th Amendment to the
Constitution, was passed by both houses of the Parliament
unanimously early July.
</P>
<P>
It restrains members of the Parliament from breaching party
discipline, code of conduct and declared policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
