<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Buddhism in Prime  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Buddhist scripture publishing house has been set up in Lhasa,
and almost every monastery has a copy of the Tibetan Kagyur of the
Tripitaka. A large number of other religious classics are also
back in print.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan Buddhism has a greater influence outside Tibet now,
reaching more than 20 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Many religious people from around the world visit Tibet's
sacred places, and more Tibetans are going abroad, as well as
taking an active part in state and government affairs. Now, 600
Buddhists in Tibet hold posts in the Regional People's Congress or
the Regional Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
"The government treats all Tibetan Buddhist sects alike, and
gives them equal respect and protection," said Gabsang Gya, who is
writing a book on Tibetan Buddhist sects. And different sects live
together harmoniously, even in the same monastery.
</P>
<P>
Seven million people have made a pilgrimage to the Johkang
Monastery in Lhasa since 1991, and more than a million this year.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Panchen Lama, who was chosen, ordained and enthroned
in strict accordance with the religious protocol and historical
practices of Tibetan Buddhism, is supported by believers, the
scholar said.
</P>
<P>
Gabsang Gya concluded "The government has provided a fine
environment for the development of Tibetan Buddhism."  
</P>
</TEXT>
