<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Agrees to Fund All Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
agreed to fund all political parties in the country as a way to
foster the growth of five-year-old multi-partyism, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government has also agreed that an election timetable,
including the date of the impending poll, be set out by the
Electoral Commission after the dissolution of the parliament,
said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The government's move came following a recommendation of this
kind from the Inter-Parties Governmental Group comprising
lawmakers from both the ruling party and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Only parties that qualify as parliamentary parties will
receive money from the consolidated fund, which will be audited
by the Controller and Auditor-General, according to a document
issued by Attorney-General Amos Wako Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amount for each party will be determined by the number of
seats it has in the parliament, said the paper. It will be
perused by the IPPG sub-committees before going to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government has also pledged to provide security to all
presidential candidates if they apply in writing.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties are reportedly to hold several caucuses
today to nominate names of an additional 10 members of the
Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said it has been agreed that FORD-Kenya,
FORD-Asili and the Democratic Party will each forward three names
and IPPG Co-ordinating Committee Secretary George Anyona's Kenya
Social Congress party one person.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 21 registered political parties in the
eastern African country but only six in the parliament where the
ruling Kenya African National Union enjoys a sweeping majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
