<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Overpopulation, Main Hurdle to Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Overpopulation remains a main
hurdle to the development of the South Asian countries and common
efforts should be made to overcome poverty, illiteracy and
overpopulation in the region.
</P>
<P>
This view was echoed among Speakers from Pakistan, India,
Bangladesh, the Maldives, Bhutan, Nepal and Sri Lanka at a
three-day conference of speakers and parliamentarians of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) which concluded
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Speakers pointed out that overpopulation, illiteracy and
poverty have defied vast natural and human resources, and deprived
one fifth of humanity of fruits of progress.
</P>
<P>
South Asia accounts for only 3.3 percent of the world's land
surface, but its population of 1.2 billion is 20 percent of the
world's total and its population growth rate is the highest in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the region is the abode for nearly half of the
world's illiterate, and about 160 million children in the region
are suffering from malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
Noting South Asia is the poorest part of the world, the
Speakers said that overpopulation, poverty, low literacy and
shortage of basic amenities pose a big threat to the social and
economic order in the region's countries.
</P>
<P>
They called for the SAARC countries to work together to achieve
peace, prosperity and people's development, which are the SAARC's
objectives.
</P>
<P>
For economic growth, said the Speakers, the international trade
is a proven strategy. "We should concentrate in this area, keeping
aside our political differences for the moment," one of them
stressed.
</P>
<P>
They urged the SAARC countries to focus on tackling the issues
of overpopulation and poverty by addressing them at both
governmental and people's levels.
</P>
<P>
They also called for promoting economic cooperation among the
SAARC member countries and active role from all the member
countries in handling the problems in a concerted manner.
</P>
<P>
With the promotion of people-to-people contacts and population
welfare and development as the focal subject, the three-day
conference unanimously approved the recommendations made by the
participants.
</P>
<P>
It called on the parliaments and parliamentarians to play an
active role in tackling the issues of overpopulation, illiteracy
and poverty in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
