<HEADLINE> Kenya's Birth Rate Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's population growth rate
fell from 3.8 percent in the mid-eighties to 2.7 percent in mid
1996, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The drop, the biggest in the sub-Saharan Africa, is partly due
to the fact that more and more Kenyan women, making up 37 percent
in 1997, now use modern family planning methods, said U.S. Agency
for International Development Mission chief George Jones.
</P>
<P>
Education is playing a leading role in downing the birth rate
in the eastern African country as it helps people make informed
choices on family planning methods, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, infant mortality has dropped from 69 per 1000
children in 1970 to 60 per 1,000 currently due to the spread of
education, he said in Embu, central Kenya, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Economic conditions and population growth have adversely
affected the government's ability to provide free health
services, according to the press report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
