<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Getting New Hygiene Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- In a remote village in central
China's Hunan province, a farmer says that if they want to lead a
better life, they, first of all, must have a good health.,
</P>
<P>
In this remote village, 10 children hold out their hands to
display fingernails neatly cut. This makes provincial health
officials happy, because Chinese farmers had no health habits in
the past. They drank unboiled water, many people shared a single
towel, and they seldom brushed their teeth.
</P>
<P>
Then, three years ago, the Chinese government began an
education campaign for its 900 million farmers to give them a
better sense of the need for hygiene and better health habits.
</P>
<P>
In Hunan's Luxi county, a local hospital did a survey in 1990
and found that 71.4 percent of the people had roundworms, and
every summer, malaria and similar diseases were quite common.
</P>
<P>
Over the past seven years, the local government has helped
farmers get greater access to clean water, and health education
films have been shown and health classes opened in local schools.
</P>
<P>
As a result, half the farmers in Luxi's town of Pushi have
changed their habits, and improved health has helped them earn
more. In 1996, the average income in the town was 2,100 yuan, five
times the figure of seven years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
