<HEADLINE> Tibet Through Foreign Eyes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Geoff Bailey, an Australian
studying at Tibet University, says he's surprised at the number of
cars on the streets of Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, not only Chinese, but foreign types as well.
</P>
<P>
Geoff has been studying the Tibetan language for one and a half
years, but says he didn't think life here would be very
convenient, but it turned out that the local people are enjoying a
fairly good life.
</P>
<P>
He and his wife have visited quite a few Tibetan families and
have found living conditions improving daily, even if sanitary
conditions need some improvement. Many locals live in good
buildings and have electric household appliances.
</P>
<P>
The couple like Lhasa's marketplace, where clothes are good
quality and cheap, and food market where they can find many kinds
of their favorites.
</P>
<P>
Geoff says he's satisfied with communications in Lhasa and
thinks they're developing fast. A parcel from his hometown takes
about 10 days and phone calls to other parts of the world are
fairly easy.
</P>
<P>
The couple are fascinated by the plateau's snow-covered
mountains, grassland, and lakes that are not polluted, and they
like to ride bicycles.
</P>
<P>
They also care about the traditional culture and have visited
the Potala and the Johkang and Norbu Lingka monasteries to watch
people from neighboring provinces come for religious activities.
Tibetan families take their tents, food, and musical instruments
to Norbu Lingka or parks in Lhasa, wearing Tibetan or
Western-style clothes or Chinese tunics, and they seem to be
content with their lives, he says.
</P>
<P>
The couple say they're satisfied with the public security in
Lhasa and seldom hear of violent incidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
