<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Lawmakers Examine Draft Forestry Amendments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislators are
examining draft amendments to the 12-year-old Forestry Law to protect
timber resources in this forest-deficient country.
</P>
<P>
The members of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC) today began to examine proposed amendments to the
existing law during their bimonthly meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The draft suggests an article governing the transfer of the
right to use woods and trees, which can provide terms for
cooperative reforestation. It also bans approval by local
authorities for logging state-owned forests, which accounts for
only 3.3 percent of the world forestry acreage.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, indiscriminate local certifications have
reduced the nation's forest acreage. The present Forestry Law
stipulates that only governments above the county level can
authorize certificates for logging.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a new clause has been proposed for planting and
managing shelter-forests, conserving water and preventing soil
erosion.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, the country will compensate those who
manage shelter forests.
</P>
<P>
To protect the diversity of plant resources, China will ban or
limit the export of precious trees if the top legislature approves
the amendments.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the implementation of various stipulations of the
Forestry Law, the country will also set up police departments in
forestry areas to maintain social order, protect forestry
resources and prevent forestry fires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
