<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Two Patients Infected with HIV-Tainted Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Two patients have been
infected with the Human Immuno-deficiency Virus (HIV) which causes
AIDS because the blood they received in a hospital here was
tainted, the Straits Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first such case in Singapore and the Singapore
Government has said that it would pay for all the medical expenses
of the two patients who were given the HIV-tainted blood.
</P>
<P>
The report said that police are investigating the case to see
if the donor of the tainted blood ought to be prosecuted. The
HIV-infected blood came from a man who had been a regular blood
donor at the Singapore Blood Transfusion Service since July last
year.
</P>
<P>
Tests on blood he gave in June this year did not show the HIV,
because he made the donation during what is called the "window
period" of about three weeks after infection, when the virus does
not show up in available tests. But he was infected at the time,
and the blood was transfused to the two patients, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The truth was found out only later in September when the man
turned up again to make a sixth donation, and this time the tests
showed that he was HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
The Healthy Ministry said in a statement that it is the first
case in almost 742,000 blood donations made in Singapore since
1985 when HIV screening of blood donors was started.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry said that the victims and their families were
devastated by the discovery. The Government has promised that "all
necessary medical treatment and support" would be given to the
victims. Besides, the victims, together with their family members,
were receiving counseling to cope with the horrifying discovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
