<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Debt Up 8.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese inland had 118.64
billion U.S. dollars in outstanding foreign debt by the end of
June, up 8.3 percent from a year ago, according to the latest
statistics of the State Administration of Foreign Exchange.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that the value of outstanding medium- and
long-term debt rose 7.1 percent to 104.96 billion
U.S. dollars by June, accounting for 88.5 percent of the total,
while that of short-term debt went up 17.9 percent to 13.68
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China borrowed 16.6 billion U.S. dollars in new foreign debt in
the first half of this year, up 11 percent from the same period of
last year. Meanwhile, it repaid 18.1 billion U.S. dollars in
principal and interests, a rise of 52.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis of all foreign debt outstanding by June,
34.8 billion U.S. dollars were owed by the ministries and
other departments of the State Council, 40.35 billion U.S. dollars by
Chinese-funded financial institutions, 1.48 billion U.S. dollars by
leasing companies, 29.58 billion U.S. dollars by foreign-funded
enterprises, and 12.35 billion U.S. dollars by domestic
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
