<HEADLINE> China Railway to Computerize Ticketing in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China is building a
computerized national train ticket network to better handle the
growing passenger traffic.
</P>
<P>
The network, to link 278 major localities including Hong Kong,
should be completed by the end of 1998, according to a national
conference on booking train tickets held here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since the Ministry of Railways initiated the plan last May,
software has been developed to enable the booking system to cover
21 railway stations around Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai and Jinan regional centers will join the network
by the end of this year. Booking services for express train
stations along four railway trunks and 44 other major railway
stations will also be computerized.
</P>
<P>
By next June, 14 regional centers will be set up, computerizing
the booking service of four railway arteries: Beijing-Guangzhou,
Beijing-Shanghai, Beijing-Harbin and Lianyungang-Lanzhou.
</P>
<P>
The last 11 regional centers, including Hong Kong, are expected
to join the network by 1998.  
</P>
