<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judges Issue in Pakistan Likely to Be Settled Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The tussle between the
government and the Supreme Court over the appointment of judges
seemed to be resolved after an unprecedented meeting at the
presidency late last night.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which started at nine o'clock Tuesday evening and
lasted about three and a half hours, was called by President
Farooq Leghari and attended by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, Chief
of Army Staff General Jehangir Karamat and Chief Justice Sajjad
Ali Shah.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the first time in Pakistan's history that
heads of the executive, the judiciary and the army met in this
manner to head off an impending clash between different state
institutions.
</P>
<P>
According to government sources, the meeting Tuesday night has
hammered out a "mutually acceptable solution" to the problem.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided not to bring up the issue in the
National Assembly session scheduled for Wednesday evening and the
details of the final settlement are expected to be announced by
the government today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the four powerful men was "positive,
constructive and was held in a cordial atmosphere," the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
There are reports that last night's meeting had worked out a
settlement between the government and the judiciary and the
dispute had been buried. The question of the number of judges to
be elevated had also been settled.
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary and unprecedented meeting was held to arrest
the crisis situation arising from the dispute between the
government and the Chief Justice on the elevation of five judges
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
since the negotiations between the government and the Chief
Justice had reached point of no return with the government going
ahead with legislation on fixing the strength of Supreme Court
judges, President Leghari finally interfered to make last ditch
efforts to resolve the issue outside the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government had prepared its strategy after taking
its allied parties into confidence regarding its proposed
legislation to reduce the sanctioned strength of judges in the
Supreme Court. However, the plan was canceled late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Other sources said that the government has made no final
decisions about its strategy and kept its options open leaving
them on developments today.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court will pass final order on the stay application
praying for suspension of the operation of the Anti-Defection Law
today, only hours before the National Assembly session in which
the government is likely to table a bill relating to the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Defection Law, or the 14th amendment to the
Constitution, passed unanimously by both houses of the parliament
early July restrains members of the parliament from breaching
party discipline, code of conduct and declared policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
