<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Strategic Dialogue "Very Important": Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said on Tuesday that President Bill Clinton is
looking forward to a summit with Chinese President Jiang Zemin,
and to continuing a strategic dialogue with China.
</P>
<P>
She made this remark at a special briefing at the State
Department right after the Chinese head of state arrived here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
She then went to the Blair House, where Jiang Zemin is staying
during his visit here, to express her welcome to her
Chinese guest.
</P>
<P>
"I think that it's very important to have this strategic
dialogue and talk about a whole set of issues that affect regional
stability," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the Clinton administration hopes "for some
progress" through the U.S.-China summit in expanding cooperation
in areas of shared interest.
</P>
<P>
Albright stressed that the U.S. policy of engagement with China
"is a long-term process", in which the U.S. would make "active
search for areas where we can work with China for our own benefit
and that of the region and the world," while talking "frankly
about difference" with China.
</P>
<P>
She reaffirmed, however, that the U.S. relationship with China
should not be held hostage to any one single issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
