<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Conditions Improving in Ethnic Minority Regions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China's ethnic minority areas
have achieved amazing progress in turning their rich resources to
economic advantage in the last couple of years, a senior government
official reported to a recent conference.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) of areas inhabited by ethnic
minorities in China has grown at an average annual rate of 12.7
percent in the past five years, higher than the national average,
Tudao Doje, vice minister of the State Nationalities Affairs
Commission, told a national conference on ethnic development in
Beihai, a port city in southern China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The economic strength of ethnic minority regions has greatly
improved with fixed assets increasing by 337.5 billion yuan in the
1992-96 period, mainly as a result of tapping their natural
resources, Tudao said.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output rose from 188 billion yuan to 488.5 billion
yuan, representing an annual growth of 14 percent, he said. Tudao
credited the achievement to new trends in fully exploiting natural
resources in such regions.
</P>
<P>
The majority of China's minorities live in the Xinjiang Uygur,
Tibet, Inner Mongolia, Guangxi Zhuang and Ningxia Hui autonomous
regions, 13 autonomous prefectures and 121 autonomous counties
with a combined population of 103 million.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth of these regions long has lagged behind that of
other parts of the country because of poor transportation,
inadequate funding and a lack of technical expertise.
</P>
<P>
The central government's new policy of speeding up economic
development in central and western China combined with a market
economy have provided the impetus for rapid growth in ethnic
minority regions, Tudao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Improving in Ethnic Minority Regions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the 1990-96 period, Inner Mongolia, which has a verified
coal reserve of 217 billion tons, provided Beijing with 12.4
billion kilowatt-hours of electricity, 25 percent of the city's
demand.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with a new government strategy, Inner Mongolia is
burning coal to produce electricity. This strategy has turned
Inner Mongolia from an electricity importer to exporter and has
accelerated its process of industrialization.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in northwestern China is
emerging as a leading oil producer in the country. The region has
succeeded in increasing its oil output from 5.5 million tons in
1986 to last year's 14.7 million tons. Three petro-chemical
plants have been built. The output from oil accounts for 30
percent of the region's total industrial production.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang also leads the country in both the total outout and
unit yield of cotton.
</P>
<P>
The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has put into operation the
Nanning-Kunming Railway line and airports in the cities of Guilin
and Liuzhou since the region was designated in 1992 as a major
outlet on the sea in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Exploitation of natural resources in ethnic minority regions
will help to accelerate their economic growth, enhance unity among
people of various ethnic groups and narrow the gap between these
regions and economically developed areas, Tudao said.
</P>
<P>
Resource-tapping has combined the efforts of people in the
eastern and western parts of the country and of Han and ethnic
minorities. More than 20,000 township-run enterprises in eastern
China have invested 30 billion yuan in developing untapped
resources in the central and western parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Official 1996 statistics show that the range of the increase in
per capita net income of farmers in China's minority-inhabited
central and western parts surpassed that in the income of farmers
on the eastern coast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
