<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Ready to Offer $10 Bln in Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
has confirmed that Singapore is ready to offer 10 billion U.S.
Dollars in assistance to help restore confidence in the Indonesian
economy, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 10 billion U.S. Dollars, Soeharto said Tuesday in
Pasuruan, East Java, 5 billion U.S. Dollars would be standby loans
to strengthen the country's foreign exchange reserves and another
5 billion U.S. Dollars would be used to buy rupiahs to help the
country re-build public confidence in its currency.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto said rupiah bought by Singapore would remain in
control of Bank Indonesia, the central bank, to extend credit
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The offer was made by Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
during his visit here on October 21. No figures were given then on
the amount of aid.
</P>
<P>
Similar pledge was also made by Malaysia with Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim committing one billion U.S. Dollar Monday
in standby loans to help Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, informed sources at the State Secretariat said
Tuesday that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto would hold
telephone discussions with President Soeharto today on the current
crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Indonesian government had decided to
ask for financial assistance from international financial
institutions, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the
World Bank and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Soeharto surprised the market on Tuesday by saying that
Indonesia was not seeking financial aid from the IMF but only
advice on some economic reform packages already prepared by the
government.
</P>
<P>
"Don't misunderstand, we're not asking for money, we've
already set up out own (reform) programs, and we've asked IMF to
look at them because of their experience," Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto also asserted that IMF did not insist on any
conditionality to restore confidence in the rupiah which has
dropped by about 50 percent against the U.S. Dollar since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The president said the monetary crisis the country had suffered
for months so far was not because the country's economic
fundamentals were weak but because the impact of the monetary
crisis in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's economic fundamentals were quite strong
with foreign exchange reserve amounting to 22 billion U.S. Dollars
which was enough for five month imports.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate meanwhile remained below 10 percent while
economy grew by seven to eight percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have to face the crisis calmly and with full
self-confidence," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
