<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Helps Impoverished Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Since 1984, 2.41 billion yuan
(about 300 million U.S. dollars) has been invested in impoverished
areas of north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Regions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the region has built more than 10,000
kilometers of roads and increased irrigated areas by 200,000
hectares and transformed 66,000 hectares of medium- and low-yield
fields.
</P>
<P>
Potable water projects have been a high priority for the region
with 1.61 million farmers and 5.73 million head of livestock in
impoverished areas now having access to high-quality drinking
water. The general level of farmers' health has markedly improved,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
To develop animal husbandry, the regional government has
provided livestock for herdsmen living in impoverished areas.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 3.8 million farmers have escaped poverty. Grain
output for the 50 poorest counties topped 10 billion kilograms in
1996, increasing by 6 billion kilograms over the 1984 figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
