<HEADLINE> South China Province Sets Up New Poverty Elimination Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The provincial government of
China's southernmost island province of Hainan has worked out goals
for eliminating poverty.
</P>
<P>
It plans to help 160,000 of the 450,000 poor people in Hainan
get rid of poverty this year, by raising their per-capital income
by at least 100 yuan, and the reamaining 290,000 will be rid of
poverty by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the province has put 232 million yuan into poverty
eradication and has brought the number of its poor people to the
present figure from 1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
In the past seven years, Hainan has built 400 water
conservation projects and 2,430 drinking water projects in rual areas.
</P>
<P>
The power generating capacity has increased by 760,000 kw and
922 km of roads have been built.
</P>
<P>
The province has paid attention to the agricultural development
and the better use of local resources in backward areas. It has
set up 212 agricultural production bases and developed 26,700
ha. of land for tropical plant cultivation in impoverished areas.
</P>
<P>
Scientific farming has been another important part of the
drive. Hainan has run training courses for 160,000 farmers.
</P>
</TEXT>
