<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Stock Plunges Unlikely to Affect China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The recent across-the-board
plunges in major stock indices worldwide will not affect China's
"A share" market, according to a report by the Shanghai Securities
News today.
</P>
<P>
The fact that A shares are not open to overseas investors means
that stock market volatility in other parts of the world will not
affect China, said the report citing Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
There are two separate stock markets in China. The A share
market is for domestic investors only, while the B share market is
reserved for overseas buyers.
</P>
<P>
Pan Yingli, a professor in international finance, said that
China's not-yet-open capital market will prevent the A share
market from being affected by the wild fluctuations of other world
markets.
</P>
<P>
The major stock indices in Hong Kong, New York, London, Tokyo,
Seoul, Paris, Frankfurt and Sydney have dived in recent days.
</P>
<P>
Pan, a professor with the Shanghai-based East China Teachers'
University, said the performance of China's A share market is
determined by the fundamentals of the Chinese mainland and by
market confidence.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy has been sound in recent years, the experts
said, with the monthly inflation rate down to almost nothing, and
investor confidence remaining stable.
</P>
<P>
Gu Mingde, a researcher at the Shanghai Branch of the People's
Bank of China, the central bank, acknowledged that the recent
stock plunges in other parts of the world may affect the markets
of the B shares and H shares, which refer to those listed in Hong
Kong by inland Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
"The impact on A shares will be very limited," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese currency is still not convertible under the capital
account, making it virtually impossible for international
speculators to launch an attack on the Chinese stock market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Both experts say that interest rate cuts this month will
benefit the development of the stock market in the long term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
