<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, October 29 (Xinhua) -- With about 20 billion U.S.
dollars in foreign loans owed by 250 private businesses coming due
next year, the Thai Bankers' Association (TBA) is urging to create
a special forum to negotiate extensions with some 150 foreign
creditors, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The sum is part of the foreign loans totaling 71 billion U.S.
dollars owed by Thai private borrowers.
</P>
<P>
If the loans are recalled without extensions, tight liquidity
in the country would worsen further, TBA Chairman Olarn Chaipravat
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, Olarn said the Thai government must act as a
core in organizing a forum for talks with foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
In July total capital outflows amounted to 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars, rising to 3.5 billion U.S. dollars in August. In the
fourth quarter of this year, at least 2 billion U.S. dollars will
leave the country, Olarn said.  
