<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Expects 4 Percent GDP Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria expects a four percent
gross domestic product (GDP) growth for 1998, Financial Minister
Muravei Radev announced today.
</P>
<P>
The budget draft approved by the government today envisages an
annual inflation rate of 35 percent and a 42 percent increase in
the average wage for next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Radev told a press conference that the GDP is likely to
decline by 6-8 percent this year and the accumulated inflation
rate will reach six percent.
</P>
<P>
The monthly average pay is 125,000 lev (78 U.S. dollars) this
year and will rise to 177,000 lev (110 dollars) in 1998, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Among the 8.37 million population, 1.5 million people were on
pay rolls and 2.4 million people received pensions from the
government, he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 600,000 people were jobless. Radev said that the
government would introduce social reform on employment to address
the problem.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal deficit would be four percent of the GDP this year
and it would fall to two percent next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The deficit would be filled up by revenues collected from
privatization, which would amount to 540 billion lev (337.5
million dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The international balance of payments will be 175 million
dollars in favor of Bulgaria and it will reach 350 million dollars
in 1999, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
