<HEADLINE> Brazil Rejects Unilateral Trade Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANACASTE, Costa Rica, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Brazil today
rejected any possible unilateral restrictions on trade after some
U.S. sectors requested to impose sanctions against some developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Jose Botafogo, head of the Brazilian delegation to the
negotiations on the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) in
Guanacaste, said the South American countries would oppose any attempt
to make environmental and social demands as an excuse to impose
restrictions on products of other countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. businessmen have said low salaries and assets in the Latin
American countries would make U.S. goods less competitive in their
markets.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 34 American countries will attend the
meeting to discuss the definitive agenda for the establishment of
FTAA here.
</P>
<P>
Botafogo also said the process for regional integration must be
equilibrated for all the would-be member countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States and Canada will negotiate the opening
of the agricultural market, which Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay, the four Southern Common Market (Mercosur) members, are
interested in, since they have faced a series of commercial
barriers to the U.S. and Canadian market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
