<TEXT>
<P>
GUANACASTE, Costa Rica, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen from
the Central American countries asked today for a preferential
treatment during a meeting on the establishment of the Free Trade
Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 34 western hemisphere countries gathered
here to define the agenda for the Americas' commercial
integration.
</P>
<P>
Central American Federation of Business President Samuel
Yankelewits asserted that "the big countries of the continent like
the United States, Brazil or Argentina should not pretend to establish
similar rules for all the 34 nations."
</P>
<P>
Yankelewits noted the only possibility for small economies to do
well in an integrated market is to give considerations to their
special conditions.
</P>
<P>
For Central American businessmen, the preferential treatment,
technical aid and financing are basic, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
A differentiated treatment is the key to counter the structural
problems undermining the competitiveness of Central American
economies, he said. 
</P>
