<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China will organize
special-mission fire brigades in 30 large cities capable of
handling fires caused by chemical explosion and combating spills
of dangerous gas or nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
An investment of 160 million yuan (nearly 19.3 million US
dollars) allocated by the State Planning Commission and the
Ministry of Finance, together with another 480 million yuan-worth
of local investment, will be poured into fire control bodies in
Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Chongqing, Harbin and other big
cities, said Yang Huanning, assistant minister in charge of public
security.
</P>
<P>
The total investment will pay for poisonous gas and chemical
monitors, and relevant facilities, and telecommunications
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The country's fire brigades have dealt with chemical spills and
other emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's fire groups completed 617 special missions last
year, and the Dalian fire department has set up a database of
special missions. 
