<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Intensifies Drug Trafficking Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian Interior Ministry
is going to step up efforts to deal with increasingly serious
drug-related crimes in the country.
</P>
<P>
About 80 per cent of the drugs sold in Europe passed along the
Balkan route and through Bulgaria, Interior Ministry Chief
Secretary General Bozhidar Popov told a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Heroin accounted for the bulk of the drugs trafficked through
Bulgaria but the quantities of cocaine, marihuana, hasheesh and
psychotropic substances were also increasing.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year Bulgarian customs
officials seized 71 per cent more heroin and over 140 times more
hasheesh than in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
More Bulgarians were involved in drug trafficking. They used to
play a supporting role but had recently joined in setting up
channels, albeit under the leadership of more powerful
international groupings, General Popov said.
</P>
<P>
Some firms engaged in drug trafficking and sales under the
cover of trade and mediation activities.
</P>
<P>
To combat the crimes, the Interior Ministry has adopted such
measures as amending the penal code, implanting police agents in
the drug-trafficking groupings and undertaking broader cooperation
with foreign special services.
</P>
<P>
In addition, special units were set up with regional
directorates of the interior on September 1 to combat drug pushers
in smaller towns, General Popov said.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that 116 persons were arrested in 1996-1997 for
involvement in drug trafficking and about 99 cases have been
opened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
