<HEADLINE> Tibet Has Good Harvest This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Grain and rapeseed output in
China's Tibet Autonomous Region is expected to be 800,000 tons and
38,500 tons respectively this year, up 5.5 percent and 11.1
percent over last year, according to the Agriculture and Animal
Husbandry Bureau of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita income of farmers and herdsmen may reach 1,040 yuan,
(about 127 US dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
The region has built 13,000 irrigation channels and 5,200 large
and small reservoirs in the past 10 years, and since the 1990s, the
central government has put 2.2 billion yuan into developing the
Yarlung Zengbo, Nyangqu, and Lhasa river valleys. This has
resulted in an annual increase of 52,000 tons of wheat and 1,672
tons of rapeseed.
</P>
<P>
The use of tractors and quality seeds also contributed to the
good harvest, an agriculture and animal husbandry official said.
</P>
<P>
To increase the use of science and technology in farming,
training classes are held for 200,000 farmers each year and 30
percent of farmers have acquired regular farming skills, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
