<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Peru Loses 290,000 Hectares of Forests Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Peru loses about 290,000 hectares
of forests each year due to natural disasters and indiscriminate
exploitation, causing precious vegetal species to disappear, a
Peruvian biologist said today.
</P>
<P>
Jose Rios, dean of School of Biology of the National University
of Agriculture (NUA), said Peru has already lost 8 million
hectares of forests, and one of the main causes is the lack of an
adequate government control to help regeneration of natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
He said poverty also led to the deforestation, because the
population uses lands for agriculture and cattle breeding
irrationally, with no planning at all and with no law enacted to
protect the natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The conflagration in the area of Machu Picchu earlier this year
engulfed 600 hectares of forests, which will take 15 to 20 years
to restore the areas devastated, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the most endangered species are cedar, mahogany,
cinchona and chestnut.
</P>
<P>
The NUA has signed an agreement with a U.S. university to
install a system to detect fires in forests in the Peruvian and
Brazilian Amazon, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, October 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- About 40 people were feared killed when a bus
plunged into a river in India's northern state of Himachal Pradesh
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 people were reportedly aboard the ill-fated bus
when the tragedy took place, the Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
Five people, who swam to safety, said the remaining passengers
were trapped in the bus which was completely submerged under the
gushing water of the river. (India-Accident)
</P>
