<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Standards for Quality Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China on Tuesday issued a set
of rules requiring large and medium-sized State-owned retailers to
employ special supervisors with official qualifications to further
ensure commodity quality.
</P>
<P>
The rules, jointly issued by the Ministry of Internal Trade and
the State Bureau of Technical Supervision, says full-time or
part-time supervisors are a must for large and medium-sized
State-owned retailers.
</P>
<P>
"China has about 50,000 large and medium-sized State-owned
retail businesses whose annual sales volume is above 40 million
yuan (4.8 million US dollars) each, and all of them have assigned
staff to be responsible for commodity quality supervision," said
Zhang Huiling, an official with the Ministry of Internal Trade.
</P>
<P>
"We have drafted the rules to help improve the quality of the
market commodity supervisors and standardize the current market
supervision of commodity quality, labelling and metrology, and
better protect the legal interests of consumers," today's China
Daily quoted Zhang as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said the new rules will help maintain a normal order of
commodity distribution by improving the "immunity of the markets"
from the entry of fake goods and substandard products.
</P>
<P>
According to the new rules, commodity supervisors will have the
right to ask commodity purchasers to refuse to sign contracts that
do not conform to the requirements of the contract acceptance
system.
</P>
<P>
They have the right to stop the sale of commodities with
quality problems and involve themselves in the investigation and
settlement of commodity disputes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0269 </DOCNO>
