<HEADLINE> Rural Enterprises Boom Under Legal Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China's township enterprise
sector, a pillar of the rural economy, has grown rapidly in
the last decade and now counts more than 23 million firms,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Regulated by the Law on Township Enterprises, these firms are
expected to continue to develop favorably, said Zong Jinyao,
deputy director of the Township Enterprises Bureau under the
Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The law, promulgated on October 29, 1996 and effective from
January 1 this year, aims to direct support, regulate and promote
the development of rural firms, which account for nearly half of
China's industrial output and provide one-third of the country's
exports.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, 15 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have issued local circulars promoting the reform
and development of township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu Province has vowed to support the development of key
rural enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
Many provinces and municipalities have set up rural firm
development funds under the Law and others are preparing to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auction Business Becoming More Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Auctioneering in China is
becoming more conventional and is expected to become a major means
of dealing with idle State-owned property in restructuring that
sector, Zhao Jie, director of the Market Department of the
Ministry of Internal Trade, told Xinhua recently.
</P>
<P>
Auctioneers were closed down in the 1950s for political reasons,
but, in 1986, the first auctioneers opened for business in
Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong province, Zhao explained, and
there are now 1,000 auction houses across the country, employing
200,000 people. These are mostly in big cities and they do 10
billion yuan in business annually.
</P>
<P>
When they started, Zhao noted, auctioneers mainly handled goods
confiscated by the authorities or artworks, but now they are
handling a dozen different items, even property rights transfers.
</P>
<P>
The Auction Law took effect on January 1 this year, and there
are other laws and rules for regulating the business. China has
tried to standardize it and to improve the level of people working
in the business, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The auction business has also helped enliven the art market and
has caused many Chinese cultural relics to be returned from
abroad, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhao pointed out the business is still very
small when compared with other countries, so there are plans to
make bigger auction houses through mergers or other means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
