<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Financial Institutions Important in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Overseas banks have become an
important force in the economic development of Shanghai, China's
largest industrial city.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that overseas financial institutions have
set up 52 operational agencies and more than 150 representative
offices in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The 200-plus financial institutions in Shanghai account for
more than one third of all overseas financial institutions in
China.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also indicate that the 52 operational overseas
financial institutions have more than 15 billion US dollars in
total assets.
</P>
<P>
The nine overseas banks approved by the People's Bank of China,
the country's central bank, to deal in the Chinese yuan on a trial
basis, including the Citibank and the Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corp, have all moved their Shanghai branches to Pudong, a
rising financial and trade district west of the Huangpu
River. Many other banks and insurance companies have followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that overseas banks have both benefited from the
rapid economic growth of Shanghai and helped introduce large
amounts of overseas funds and advanced management expertise into
Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang to Absorb Foreign Funds in Mining Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- Absorbing and utilizing foreign
funds effectively is the key to improving the mining industry in
Heilongjiang province, said a provincial government official.
</P>
<P>
The mining industrial output for 1996 in Heilongjiang Province,
rich in mineral resources, was 60 billion yuan (7.5 billion
U.S. dollars), second in the country.
</P>
<P>
Though the mining industry has become a pillar industry in the
province, its rigid economic structure would restrict sustainable
development of the economy, said Zhang Chengyi, vice-governor of
the province.
</P>
<P>
The province's resources include 131 kinds of minerals which
are distributed in 3,102 locations. Among them, 73 kinds have
proven deposits, 17 of which are in the top three of the nation
and 38 are first in the northeast provinces.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the province has exploited only 39 kinds of
minerals including oil, coal, and gold. Others remain
unexploited. Few foreign funds have been invested in the mining
industry.
</P>
<P>
To sustain development of the mining industry, Zhang said, the
province needs foreign investment, advanced technology and
expertise, and reforms in the mining industry's structure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Province Speeds up Highway Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, October 29 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
plans to speed up construction of high-speed roads, especially
expressways.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, the province will complete its east-west and
north-south network with provincial capital Jinan at the hub.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the Provincial Department of
Communications, Shandong will build 1,590 kilometers of
expressways in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The network will extend from Jinan west to the border of
Shandong and Hebei provinces, east to the coastal cities of Yantai
and Weihai, south to Shanghai and Fuzhou, capital of Fujian
Province.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of the network, Jinan will be connected to most
major cities by the expressways and local roads, the official said.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, Shandong will build 3,000 kilometers of high-speed
highways and 4,500 kilometers of local roads.
</P>
<P>
China is stepping up efforts to build expressways. According to
a national plan, the country's freeway network should exceed 8,000
kilometers by 2000.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, Shandong along with Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai
municipalities and Guangdong Province will take the lead in
modernizing their highway networks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
