<HEADLINE> Female Referees to Appear in NBA Regular Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Dee Kantner and Violet Palmer
was hired by the National Basketball Association as full-time
referees, the NBA announced the news on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kantner, 36, was the supervisor of officials in the WNBA while
the 33-year-old Palmer was an official in the women's professional
league. Both have officiated women's college games.
</P>
<P>
They also officiated preseason games last season, although they
did not be on court of the regular season. They will join three
other new members of the NBA's 58-member officiatin crew.
</P>
<P>
All league teams were ordered to set aside a spare room for
female officials.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in major pro sports in the United States
that females will officiate regular season games in an all-male
league. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telegraph Losing Out In New Telecommunications Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- The telegraph is losing ground
in the telecommunications business in Beijing, as the Chinese
capital enters the information age.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Telegraph Office reports that the 400,000
telegraphs it now sends per month account for only about three
percent of its total business.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, the office sent a record three million telegraphs a
month and they accounted for half its business annually. But
telegraph business began to slip as telephones, mobile
phones, faxes, electronic data exchanges, computer communications,
and satellite communications ate their way into the market.
</P>
<P>
Some 35 percent of Beijing residents now own telephones. Last
year, the average Beijing household made or received 343
long-distance calls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971029.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
