<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: China to Achieve Zero Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 29 (Xinhua) -- China may achieve the goal of
zero population growth when its population reaches about 1.6
billion by the year 2050, a scholar from the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS) has said.
</P>
<P>
"China's population is bound to keep going up over a long
period of time, even though the country has scored notable
achievements in controlling the population increase," said Tian
Xueyuan, director of the CASS Institute of Population Science, at
a training program on family planning being held in Chongqing
Municipality.
</P>
<P>
He added that experts both at home and abroad predicted that
China's population will climb to 1.3 billion by 2000, 1.4 billion
by 2010, and may reach around 1.6 billion by 2050, the year China
can realize zero population growth.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people's income will grow by a large margin during the
next 50 years, along with the booming urbanization and
modernization, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
"All these factors will lead to a rapid consumption growth that
contributes to the conflicts between the over-population and the
lack of natural resources," said Tian. "So it is urgent for us to
seek a means of sustainable development which can save more
resources and be compatible with the population growth."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
