<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ochi Day Celebrated in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Greece today celebrated the 57th
anniversary of Ochi (No) Day with the church Te Deums, students
parades nationwide and a large military parade in the northern
port city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
On October 28, 1940, Greece was dragged into World War II after
rejecting Italian dictator Benito Mussolini's ultimatum to
surrender to the fascist forces or be invaded.
</P>
<P>
After the military parade in Thessaloniki, Greek President
Costis Stephanopoulos said that with strong armed forces capable
of confronting any designs against Greece, the country was
peacefully proceeding on the road of progress and prosperity,
looking at the future with courage and hope.
</P>
<P>
It was necessary for the younger generations to be fully
informed on the 1940 epoch, so that they too could feel the
emotion and enthusiasm with which the Greek people had hastened to
fulfill their duty of defending the homeland, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos said that the Greek
armed forces gave, with their presence, the message of certainty,
stability and calm that the Greek people should feel.
</P>
<P>
He added that they showed that they were capable of confronting
and providing what Greece and the entire region need: prosperity,
peace and progress.
</P>
<P>
Main opposition New Democracy leader Costas Karamanlis said
that the Ochi Day anniversary was a reminder that when the nation
had unity and determination, it could attain all its goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
