<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang Zemin Arrives in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin arrived here today to continue his state visit to the United
States at the invitation of President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
It is the first state visit by a Chinese head of state to the
U.S. in 12 years, a historical event seen as a milestone in the
Sino-American relations.
</P>
<P>
At the Andrews military airport, President Jiang was met by
U.S. Vice President Al Gore. Red carpets rolled down and flowers
were presented to the Chinese leader and his wife Wang Yeping. He
shook hands with the U.S. and Chinese officials present and waved
his acknowledgement to a big crowd holding the Chinese and
American national flags.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president was driven straight to the Blair House
downtown Washington where he and his wife are going to stay and
where Secretary of State Madelaine Albright was awaiting to meet
them.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is to receive a 21-gun solute welcome Wednesday morning
in the South Lawn of the White House, which is to be followed by a
summit meeting with President Clinton at noon and a state dinner
in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Upon departure from Beijing Sunday, President Jiang told the
press that he is going to discuss with President Clinton the
bilateral ties, cooperation in both bilateral and international
spheres.
</P>
<P>
"I hope and believe that my U.S. tour will produce important
results through joint efforts by both sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang flew to the American Capital, the third leg of
his current trip, from Williamsburg, a symbol of British colonial
rule in the 17th century. He also made a stopover in Honolulu,
Hawaii, after a long flight from Beijing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
His entourage -- Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
and his wife Zhou Hanqiong, special assistant Zeng Qinghong,
Director of the State Council's Foreign Affairs Office Liu
Huaqiu, special assistant Teng wensheng, Vice-Foreign Minister Li
zhaoxing, Assistant Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi and special
assistant You Xigui -- also arrived here on the same plane.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's summit meeting will be the fifth of its kind since
1993 when the two presidents met in Seattle at the APEC informal
meeting of leaders. In the following years, they met in Jakarta,
New York and Manila.
</P>
<P>
The Presidents agreed to exchange visits at their Manila summit
meeting in last November, giving a momentum to the improvement of
Sino-American relationship which turned sour following the U.S.
imposition of sanctions against China in 1989 and the invitation
to Lee Teng Hui of Taiwan to visit the United States in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Preparation has been under way since then, with both sides
making greater efforts to figure out the interests to be shared
and the differences to be ironed out.
</P>
<P>
The both sides have expressed their desire to work together on
regional and world peace and stability, non-proliferation, drugs
and crimes, economy and trade, science and technology, as well as
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
As for the differences, mainly on human rights and trade
imbalance, the two countries share the view of narrowing the gaps
through talks and negotiations rather than pointing fingers at
each other publicly.
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, the upcoming summit meeting is expected
to focus on seeking common ground for closer cooperation toward
the 21st century while trying to diminish their differences.
</P>
<P>
The current tour will also take Jiang to Philadelphia, New
York, Boston and Los Angeles before he winds up his nine-day U.S.
trip.
</P>
<P>
It has been confirmed that President Clinton will return a
visit to China next Spring, fueling optimism for future ties
between the two major countries in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
