<HEADLINE> Pentagon: Warsaw Pact Structure May Reduce NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A top U.S. Defense
Department official said today that the vast military structure
established by the Warsaw Pact during the Cold War could reduce
the cost of expanding the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
"The old Soviet-style infrastructure, while having some
defects, provides a very good foundation on which to build," said
Defense Undersecretary Walter Slocombe in his testimony to the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to vote to ratify the expansion treaty
next spring and is holding hearings into various aspects of the
expansion plan now.
</P>
<P>
Slocombe said all three nations, Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic, invited to join NATO in 1999 have made sufficient
progress on military, political, economic and social reforms.
</P>
<P>
"They are clearly ready to take the next steps to becoming full
members, accepting all the rights and responsibilities of
membership," Slocombe said.
</P>
<P>
The financial burden of the expansion of the alliance has
aroused controversies. The Pentagon estimated in February that the
total cost would be at 27 billion U.S. dollars to 35 billion
dollars over a 13-year period, much of it paid by the three new
members. The U.S. share was put at 150 million dollars to 200
million dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
But many senators have said that the cost could be much higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
