<HEADLINE> Egypt Criticizes Israeli Stance on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today criticized the Israeli stance toward peace and
emphasized that permanent peace needs a balanced approach.
</P>
<P>
"By logic and the testimony of history, peace can not be
considered permanent unless it is balanced," Moussa was quoted by
the Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He refuted the remarks made by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Tuesday that peace will not be achieved according to
the will of the Arabs but rather to Israel's security requirements.
</P>
<P>
"Eventually they (the statements) will inflame violence,"
Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
He said Netanyahu's remarks on peace in his policy address to
Israeli Knesset (parliament) Tuesday is "unrealistic" and only
expresses a "short-sighted policy of intransigence."
</P>
<P>
He warned that Netanyahu's policy of rejection of all signed
peace agreements with the Palestinians will lead to a state of
international chaos.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that Israel wants to advance the peace process,
adding peace agreements can not be fully carried out unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
He said that no more land will be handed over to the
Palestinians unless the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
fulfills its commitments to fight terror.
</P>
<P>
He also declared that Israel will continue Jewish settlement
activities in the West Bank, and Jerusalem will remain as the
unified capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have come to a crucial
crossroad as Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy has postponed his
talks with PNA chief negotiator Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) scheduled
in Washington this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
